animal.description:
My name is "Pumba" and just like my ears, my life has been up and down. You see, I was living in a shelter down south, which was very sad for me. But, I'm happy to tell you my life is on the "up", as I was one of the lucky ones chosen to be given a chance at great life in this great state of New Hampshire!

Everyone falls in love with how cute I am! Some of my favorite pastimes are snuggling on my soft blankets, playing, chasing tennis balls and I love a good chew toy! I have wonderful leash manners and everyone says I'm a joy to walk. I know some basic commands and I'm willing to learn more if you will teach me. I do love a good back & butt scratching too! In my kennel here at the shelter, I'm such a quiet, well behaved guy.

I am 2 years old, 66 lbs., neutered and current on vaccinations. My ideal home would be children 12+ who will respect my space as I get used to all my new surroundings. I sometimes feel a little afraid of some people who are too quick to approach me. I just need a little time to know that everyone loves me. I am willing to meet any potential canine siblings to see if we are compatible. As for cats. I'm not sure how I feel about this things yet!

We kindly ask, if you have questions regarding Pumba, PLEASE EMAIL:

adoption@popememorialcvhs.org

**************************************************

How To Adopt a Pet

We are currently offering adoptions by appointment only, due to the Coronavirus. The Adoption Center remains closed to drop-in visitors.

The process to schedule an appointment begins with the submission of an application, which can be found on our website. Once the application is approved, we will reach out to you to schedule an appointment. Please bear with us, the new process has slowed our response time.

If you do not see an animal that would fit into your home, we highly recommend checking our website weekly as new animals may become available. We do not offer a waitlist for specific breeds, types, etc. 

As always, adoptions are first come, first serve, meaning the applicant who is approved first gets their choice of available appointment times and thus his/her choice of animals to meet and adopt. We are not able to extend holds on any animals at this time, so we ask interested adopters to make their adoption decision during their appointment and be prepared to take their new pet home with you.

The easiest way to communicate with us with any questions is via email to: 

adoption@popememorialcvhs.org


No phone calls please - Submit an application here ----> 

https://popememorialcvhs.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Benson isn’t a big boy.  He can almost qualify for what we endearingly call a pocket shepherd, almost.  Don’t let his small stature fool you though.  He knows he’s a German Shepherd through and through.  He is loyal to his family.  That is what made it so hard for him this year when he lost them because they could no longer afford him.  He doesn’t understand how he went from a home where he had lived for all of his life to being lost in a strange place, with strange people, surrounded by so many dogs in the shelter.

Unlike other dogs who have been found as strays, with Benson, we are fortunate enough to have a little history on him.  We know he loves more than anything to be with his people.  He has been known to have a little separation anxiety; so he would need a family that can help him with that, one where he isn’t left alone for long periods.  He knows some of his commands, sit, down, and even paw.  He loves to chase any rope that you drag along the ground for him.   Since Benson has been with Coastal at the Ranch, he has bonded with some of the volunteers, and he is quick to let them know that he knows they are there.  Even from a distance, he sounds off with his bark to let them know he sees them.  He is underweight right now, but we are making sure he gets extra meals.  The stress of kennel life doesn’t help Benson, especially when he is too stressed to eat.  We know that being in a stable home is exactly what he needs.  Benson is five years old now.  This was his first Christmas without a family.  We are hoping that he can find a family soon.

.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Thank you for considering adopting one of CARA's Special pets! To apply read about our adoption policies
here
to fill out an application.
Eeries bio

Hello! My name is Eerie and I am a super SWEET and LOVABLE girl. I came to CARA as a stray with terrible skin but am now done with my treatment and look like a brand new dog! I am an energetic pup that loves to run in open areas but I also can be very lazy. I love laying on blankets and pillows, but prefer to be laying on my human. I am very respectful in a home, I know the difference between my toys and my humans toys and I have an understanding of the word "no". I also know how to sit, lay down, and stay preferably with a treat in return. Please call and ask about me, or even better come and meet me!!

Good with Adults, Good with Big dogs, Somewhat vocal, Does Good in Car, Requires a yard, Leashtrained, Likes to play with toys and chew on bones, Playful, Affectionate, Goofy, Eager To Please

If there are any questions or if she has a lot of interest I can answer any questions or write up a full list of traits/characteristics about her that I have noticed since I have had her!
And if this bio needs to be changed at all (added or rewritten) please let me know!To see more animals for adoption, please visit the CARA Website

Our adoption fees are:
Dogs: $155
Cats: $95
Puppies under 4 months: $115 plus S/N Deposit: $100
Kittens under 4 months: $70 plus S/N Deposit: $100

All pets available for adoption have been spayed or neutered (unless under 4 months please read about our adoptions
here
), are current on vaccinations and preventatives, and micro-chipped. Cats have been tested and confirmed negative for Feline AIDS and Leukemia. Dogs have been tested for heartworm disease.

Our shelter is located at 42 Deep River Rd in Sanford and is open Tues, Thurs, & Fri from 3pm - 7pm & Sat from 10-2pm (other times available by appointment). CARA's adoption process and online application can be found at
http://www.cara-nc.org/info/adoption

Please call 919-774-9433, email adoptions@cara-nc.org, or visit www.cara-nc.org for information about this or other pets available for adoption.

If you would like to adopt me or any of my friends, please visit CARA to fill out an on-line application or e-mail us at adoptions@cara-nc.org.

Every animal that comes into the CARA program is here because one or more events occurred that led to this animal needing not only a home, but a person or family to love and protect them. Each animal has been loved and cared for by a small and determined group of people who want nothing more than to know each animal is safe for the rest of his or her life. Thank you for looking to adopt!

animal.description:
BELLE UPDATE!!

Who remembers that scared and emaciated bully girl that was dumped a few weeks back!? Look at our girl now. TLC goes a long ways!!

Meet Belle aka Willow. This girl was found dumped and starving. Willow had lived a pretty hard life before coming to us. She’s only 9-12 months old and was completely terrified of humans when she first came into care. They have not been good to her so who could blame her. She was skin and bones but has filled out great over the last few weeks. Her kennel is her safe place and she willing goes in when she’s told. She also sleeps in it all night without issues and eats in it. Despite all of her issues she’s the sweetest thing and hasn’t offered up one bit of aggression. At first she was terrified of other dogs but she has grown to love to play with others and would likely do best in a home with a playmate as we feel her 4 legged foster siblings have helped her come out of her shell. She’s great with the fosters 6 year old. She has not been around cats. A home with small critters is not a good idea as she has tried to get the pet rats in her foster home. She loves to be in her fosters lap. She’s still timid with new people but does open up and want to be loved on. She needs a home that will give her patience and time to settle in. It won’t take long and she will be your best friend forever and we can promise you that. She’s doing good on house training. She has only had a few accidents if not let out right after she eats or she drinks too much water. She’s truly a great little girl. She is utd, hw neg (tested below detectable levels) and will be spayed on 1/20. 

All dogs have a $150 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $100 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

ADOPTION APPLICATION

https://form.jotform.us/70898112177159

animal.description:
Senior Hearts Rescue and Renewal is the only licensed senior dog rescue organization in Western Pennsylvania. We do not have a shelter or a public facility. ALL of our dogs reside in foster homes in the greater Pittsburgh, PA area. 

We are a 100% volunteer organization. Please respect our volunteers' time. If a dog is listed on PetFinder, he/she IS available for adoption. We cannot reply to messages, phone calls, and emails about a dog until we have received, reviewed, and approved an adoption application. 

Our ADOPTION application is found at www.seniorhearts.org Completing this application is the first step in our adoption screening process. You MUST complete the application in its entirety in order to be considered as a potential adopter.  Please select "More About Us" for further details on our adoption requirements.  You can meet a dog ONLY after we have completed our adoption approval process.

If you are looking at the dog below, it most certainly means the dog is available for adoption. We look forward to receiving your application in hopes that you are able to meet our adoption requirements and provide this dog a loving furever home.

Beabe here!  I am a 14-year young girl who weighs 8 pounds.  Yes I am just a small thing perfect to take everywhere.  I am easy going and sweet senior citizen looking for my furever home where I can comfortably spend my senior years.

I am mostly blind and going deaf but that doesn't stop me from having fun and exploring.  I am pretty low maintenance.  I am very happy to take my short walks, get a mini play session in, and relax in my bed.  If you are looking for that best friend that will give you all the unconditional love you can handle I am your girl. 

I can be adopted within a two-hour radius of Pittsburgh, PA. If you are interested in giving me a furever home, you must first complete the adoption application at www.seniorhearts.org

Beabe
xoxxo

animal.description:
Shelby is a courtesy posting for the Animal Shelter of Schoharie Valley and is not a Safe at Last dog.  So, if you are interested, please be sure to direct your inquiries to Shelby's foster mom Jill at swiffer109@yahoo.com.  Foster mom Jill is the only person who can answer your questions and/or consider you for adoption.  So, please email her at swiffer109@yahoo.com.  Many thanks for your interest.  
_______________________________________________________________________

Shelby is a lovely little 6-year-old, spayed female, Jack Russell Terrier/Chihuahua/Pittie mix.  Sadly, Shelby's owner unexpectedly passed away from covid…, and she is without any other family.  Shelby therefore will need to find a new forever home.

As to be expected, she was a bit confused, and unsure about the drastic change in her living situation; however, dogs are resilient, and she is adjusting well.  She is housebroken and trustworthy in the home when left alone.  She is also crate trained if needed.  She is actually a pretty easy-going girl in the household.

When Shelby first came into foster care after her dad passed away, she didn't have much in the way of social skills interacting with other animals – she just never had a reason to since she lived solo.  After working with her for just a very short time, she has learned and is interacting appropriately in her foster home with both her canine foster sister and resident felines. We feel that Shelby would be able to live with another dog that would match her personality type – a non-dominant/non-confrontational canine counterpart would pair best.  And dog-savvy indoor cats as she sometimes would consider chasing a kitty - but when told that is no longer appropriate, she listens very well.

Shelby would also be very happy to have her own person/people all to herself; so we will assess potential animal companions on a case-by-case basis - so long as the humans in the household are dog-savvy and committed to giving Shelby continued guidance :)

She is working on her leash reactivity towards other unknown dogs/cats, an area that just became a habit for her.  However, Shelby responds so very well to correction and redirection of undesirable behavior.  She is very food-motivated and, thus, when necessary, consistent correction & reward result in her being very readily redirected into more appropriate behavior.  

All in all, Shelby is a quite easy little house dog.  She is a bit chunky at 35 lbs – should be about 30 – so, she is a great, manageable size; although she can pull a bit on the leash.  She is fairly mellow indoors and happy to relax in her favorite chair.  She also enjoyed daily walks with her dad & she would love to continue that with her new family.

We feel Shelby would do best in a retirement style home, with not a lot of commotion going on; but she, of course, will also need activity to keep her healthy & mentally stimulated.  We feel she’d be ok with older kids who will respect what she has been through (10+ year old kids).  

Shelby is such a nice little dog who got a raw deal in losing her dad when she should have been set for the rest of her days.  She will be a great companion for the right family, and we hope you will consider her.

**if viewing on Petfinder be sure to check out her videos & extra photos at https://safeatlast.rescuegroups.org/animals/detail?AnimalID=16441968**

_______________________________________________________________________

Also, if you have any additional questions. please contact foster mom Jill (swiffer109@yahoo.com)!  And, please feel free to fill out the Safe at Last adoption application if interested, and caretaker Jill will follow up with you.  

Shelby's adoption fee is $150 - and this includes spay, rabies vaccine, distemper vaccine, lepto vaccine, dewormer (if needed), flea treatment (if needed), heartworm/lyme test, & microchip!

animal.description:
Meet BETSY!
-Female
-3 years old
-Stafford/Pitty

Betsy is:
-Loyal
-Skittish
-Dominant
-Nervous/Anxious
-Shy
-Crate trained
-Potty trained
-Leash trained
-House trained
-Good with OLDER (10+) children
-Needs to continue training around other pets

Betsy is a MAN'S best friend. After she gets comfortable with her human, she will do whatever she can to please you! She is very skittish at first and feels the need to protect her person. She has a spunky, spirited personality! She likes to be goofy, snack on cheese and lay with her people.

For almost 2 months, Betsy has been in professional training. In this training, she has learned how to walk on a leash and somewhat socialize with other dogs. She has gained so much confidence in being a dog so she will someone who is also very confident in being a leader. She is so smart and just needs someone who will continue the training and give her the time to be the best pup possible!

We have also learned that if she had a male leader, she would thrive!
She has become SO LOVED by her trainers as now she gets excited when she sees them and has been nothing but surpassing any obstacle!


Betsy's personality will be best fit with:
-A MALE owner!
-A home with NO PETS!!
-A home with a FENCED in yard
-Someone who is going to continue training and be dedicated to her
-Someone who is ready to have the most loyal companion!

**A note from foster: "Betsy was not welcomed in her previous home and she acted out as a result. Within 2 months she’s learned how to be held on a leash, how to not be reactive towards other dogs, and how to enjoy juSf being herself. She is loved at the training facility by all staff and it shows in her progress. She needs a family willing to love the good, bad, and ugly parts of her and she will be the dog that her family is looking for!"

If you believe BETSY could be your forever buddy please fill out an adoption application: https://form.jotform.com/93263081961156

IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS PLEASE EMAIL INFO@MERCYFULLPROJECTS.ORG

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Freya is a bundle of energy and an extremely sweet dog who loves to hug everyone she meets. This girl is petite - full grown and weighing in at about 38 pounds - we've taken to calling her our pocket-husky. She is smart and learns very quickly, but of course has a typical husky personality and needs plenty of attention and exercise, or that little brain will find things to do She has been exceptionally good in the house and learns quickly to be respectful of places and things that aren't to be bounded upon or chewed. She settles in at night, on her bed or yours, but likes to be active during the day. Luckily she is good at entertaining herself for short periods and will keep you laughing at her antics!

Freya needs an active household and possibly another dog buddy. Certainly no small dogs or cats, or cattle for that matter!

Full disclosure: Freya has been diagnosed with cataracts, even at her young age. The decreased vision doesn't seem to deter her, but she has been known to bump into things and sometimes has to hunt for toys with her nose and ears, which she excels at. [Cataracts is treatable by surgery but has a long recovery process and is not recommended for her at this time due to her young age. We are continuing to monitor her to see if there is progression, or best case, the progression has stopped. This is not a painful condition like glaucoma.] Her condition does not stop her from gazing lovingly into your eyes.

Freya is a real catch. Her foster mom will eventually want to adopt an older dog, otherwise she'd keep Freya, so wants to find the right, perfect home. And look at the photos - did we say she's absolutely beautiful?!!

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Gary! The first thing you might notice about me is that I am super naked at the moment! How embarrassing. I was found in a box out in the cold and it turns out that I had a problem with my skin that made all my hair fall out. A nice lady found me and now I am doing so much better. My hair is slowly growing back and I feel great! Now I am looking for my very own family.

I am the best companion dog, I like to be very close to people and other dogs at all times. My favorite activity is burrowing under blankets and snuggling on the sofa! I will sit quietly in your lap while you work and I like to be carried around. My foster mom says that she loves when I get excited and do my signature dance moves before eating or playing. I have grown accustomed to wearing sweaters and jackets and I have learned how to use a step to get onto the sofa all by myself! I give kisses to my foster fur siblings, but it takes me a little while to warm up new dogs. I have to make sure they are considerate of my small stature!

I don't really enjoy walks. It's just not my jam... there are loud noises, I'm not interested in smelling things, and it takes me forever to get anywhere. Pick me up please! Since I am so small, I prefer to do my business outside and then go right back inside where I can live my best indoor life.

I would do best in a home where I can be around my people all day and have a yard of my own. I require frequent potty breaks and I get separation anxiety when I can't be in the same room as another dog or person. I do not do well in a crate unless you would like to get into the crate with me 

If you are looking for a calm and small companion to share your day with, then I'm the one for you.

Gary is an 8 year old male chihuahua and weighs 5.5 lbs.

animal.description: Toby Tobias Tobe Tobester Tobemeister He is quite the hunk in small packaging. Toby is a very, very, loving boy who enjoys lap time whenever he’s not playing. He would do well in a home that wants to continue working on his confidence and providing a home full of love, patience, and positive reinforcement. This Toby boy wants nothing more than to please his humans. He does need to be fed and treated separately from other dog friends. He’s very gentle but will snap at other dogs who come near his food. He is good with other dogs once he’s had time to sniff. It would be best if dogs in the home were non-reactive when they first meet him. Toby deserves an owner with a soft touch as his past one was not kind to him. He is not a fan of men and he will bark at them non-stop. He is working on crate training and will cry for bit when he first goes in, but quiets down nicely. Toby enjoys playing with toys and tug-o-war with other dogs is his absolute favorite. He is polite on a leash and listens well. Due to his crying and barking when initially crated, shared walls won’t be a good match for him. Toby is shacking up in Englewood. His adoption fee is $400. REQUIREMENTS: Positive reinforcement Patient home No shared walls Teenagers or older.  You can apply for Toby at https://milehighcanine.org/forms-and-applications/mhcr-adoption-application/.

animal.description:
Because we are all volunteers, Illinois Doberman Rescue Plus only considers approved applicants to meet our orphans in our foster homes. Please read our eligibility requirements and apply on our website: www.ildoberescue.com/adopt.  After an application is submitted, additional inquiries can email dobes@ildoberescue.com.

Denning is a 1-year-old (DOB 11/18/19) cutie who came to us via a local county animal control. Like most young Dobermans we see, people underestimate how much attention a young working breed needs, so he will require an obedience commitment to ensure his success. He is always happy, so enjoy his full natural tail always wagging and pet his long, soft ears. In a temporary foster home, Denning seemed housebroken. He is very affectionate, and he loves people. He has no known history with kids, and he will likely be a big oaf and knock them over. But sturdy and resilient kids 10 and up who act respectfully around big dogs and don’t mind sharing their toys can be considered. His exuberance for life may not be appreciated by older folks who are unsteady on their feet. Denning has no history with cats, and he doesn’t like small dogs. He wants to play with dogs more his size. He now weighs 65 lbs, and will fill out some more. Like many Dobermans, Denning is very vocal, so he’s not a good candidate for condos or townhomes. As a youngster, he has a lot of energy, so he would appreciate LONG walks or a jogging partner. A quick walk around the block to potty is not enough. He is learning not to pull, but he is catching on. He enjoys a 4-ft chainlink fence at the moment. Denning is very smart and willing to please, but he just needs some direction. He’s very busy and needs a job to occupy his mind and body. His favorite toys are chewing on a Benebone or Kong or stealing a throw pillow and playing keep away.

The biographical information provided is correct to the best of our knowledge while the animal is in our care or includes what may have been provided by a previous owner. We strive to be honest and accurate, but animals can change their personalities and behavior when they settle into a new home. IDR+ makes no guarantees based on the information we observe and provide.
animal.name: Denning

animal.description: Mac is a sweet, senior guy who would rather be playing shuffleboard and reading JA Jance mysteries at a retirement village in Boca Raton than hanging out at PACC, but he's not letting that get him down. In play group, Mac mostly kept to himself, but was tolerant of other dogs greeting him. Mac has asked to have a meet-and-greet with any resident dogs before he goes home with them, just to make sure they'd be a good fit as roommates. While Mac is a bit unsure about his feelings for other dogs, he's not at all confused about his feelings for treats: He loves them. Mac would do best in a home with a secure, fenced yard and without kids, or with older kids who can understand that sometimes dogs need space. Please don't let Mac spend any more of his golden years in the shelter. If you've got some room in your home and heart for a sweet, senior looking for a soft place to rest his head, make an appointment to meet Mac today.
animal.name: MAC

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Fuego is probably between 1-2 years old and acts very much like a youngster with energetic bouts. He is slightly submissive, and does not show Alpha tendencies. He is overweight but loves walks and is very friendly and doesn't show aggression. Fuego is not super socialized, but walks well on leash and knows some commands: Leave It and Sit. His is treat motivated and eats well and doesn't seem to have any food aggression issues. He will rummage through trash if he has the opportunity.

Fuego has slight anxiety separation, but might just be from his being tossed from place to place and he is housebroken. He has great looking white teeth...no dental issues noticeable, loves to talk at times, so can sometimes be mouthy. At 82 lbs and exuberant he jumps up when playing, but he can be calmed down. Fuego does not seem to be an escape artist or shows signs of wanting to leave his current home.

He would definitely do well and be very happy in a Husky/Mal savvy home. Fuego - came a long way. Still mouthy but lets me touch and scratch him all over. Not a big fan of being picked up or grabbed by the collar. Fuego needs a savvy, strong, and confident owner to continue with training and someone who understands the difference between mouthy and biting.
animal.name: Fuego

animal.description:
Woof, woof! I'm Blackbear, a 9-month-old, 16-pound, male chihuahua mix. 

I was rescued after a truck ran over me. I had a fractured pelvis, but now I'm all better and ready to meet you! After spending three months on crate rest, I want to roam freely! I'll need some help with crate-training. I'm intelligent and observant. I taught myself how to use a puppy pad after watching my foster-sister use one! I'm loyal to my pack. I'll be at your feet when you're cooking, working, or watching tv. I have mild separation anxiety when you're gone. I'm cautious but courageous. I protect my cat sibling from the vacuum. I'll alert you when strangers are in the distance. I'm playful and energetic. I run with the big guys at the dog park. I want to play with all cats and dogs and get a little grumpy when they don't want to play with me. I enjoy tug-of-war and long walks. At home, I'm a picky eater. Outside, I forage for snacks. Please watch what I put in my mouth! I won't beg for your food, only your attention. I've never been around small children. 

I am potty trained. I am neutered, up-to-date on shots, heart worm tested and on preventative,and microchipped. I'd do best in a home that's committed to teaching and exercising me. 

My adoption fee is $150. I can go home with you on a one-week visit!

animal.description:
Please click share and help Shelby find a loving home. Taken from a neglect situation she is still healing from a bad skin infection. She will need a special diet and we are not sure if her skin condition is chronic or not yet. 

She is about 4-5years old, spayed, vaccinated and negative for disease. She is dog selective and we are not sure about cats or children. At this time she should be an only pet and go with an experienced dog owner. 

She is very people friendly. We are still getting to know her.  

All animals impounded at the shelter must be advertised in a local paper and held for a full seven days to ensure that the proper owner has an opportunity to claim their missing animal. After the 7 day holding period applications will be accepted for the animal and the animal will be adopted to the best qualified candidate which fits the needs of the animal.

All animals are spayed & neutered prior to going home unless veterinarian recommendation prohibits us from doing so.

Adoption Fees

Unaltered(Not Spayed or Neutered) Animals

Cats $70.00 Dogs $85.00 

This entitles the adopter to a martingale collar/leash for dogs or a safety collar for cats, microchip, discount voucher towards the spay or neuter and two free vaccinations at a participating veterinarian under the State of Connecticut's Animal Population Control Program. The animal will be dropped off at a veterinarian prior to adoption. Standard health testing will be performed in addition to the alter & vaccines. The new owner will be responsible for the balance at the veterinarian which ranges on average from $100.00-$200.00 depending on the animal.

Altered (Spayed/Neutered) Animals

Dogs $40.00 Cats $25.00

These animals have been spayed/neutered, vaccinated, tested for disease and microchipped which has been paid for by donation. You will also receive a martingale collar/leash for dogs or a safety collar for cats. Additional donations are appreciated.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
JCs adoption donation is $300 and he is being fostered in Central Ohio. He has been neutered, microchipped, received his rabies, distemper/parvo, bivalent canine influenza, and bordetella vaccines, tested negative for heartworms, started on prevention as well as flea prevention. JC has also had a dental cleaning. JC requires an adoptive home with a strong, verifiable veterinary medical history.

JC is a 9 yr old Cockapoo that was surrendered through no fault of his own due to his Mom having a stroke and no longer able to care for him. He does well on housetraining if kept on a schedule. JC is leash trained and enjoys going on walks. He does well in a crate trained for when you need to leave or have him in it for the night, he is a bit of an early riser and when he's ready to get out of crate will let you know. JC is currently in a home with other dogs, but truly enjoys being wit his person so we will be looking for a home where he will be an only dog. Enjoys sleeping in a bed on the floor and does not get up on furniture. Does enjoy playing with toys and chewing on nyla bones. He can reserved, likes to be picked up but very rarely jumps on lap, loves treat, a bit chubby, loves belly rubs. JC is currently on daily medications for Cushings which he takes like a champ and it is well managed. JC has done very well in rescue and adapted to the many changes due to the loss of his owner and we would love to find him his forever home where he will be a cherished family member.
PLEASE NOTE: If you are viewing this biography on a website other than the Ohio Fuzzy Pawz website, not all information transfers to partner websites in some instances. If you go to the individual webpage of our dogs, you will be able to get more information each dog.

Visual breed identification in dogs can be unreliable so, in many cases, we are only guessing at the predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

Our Adoption Process

The adoption process has several steps involved.

Please review prior to submitting an application.
Our adoption process is detailed here:

http://www.ohiofuzzypawz.com/info/adoption

Our volunteers work very diligently to process each application and we try to ensure that we are making the best match possible for each dog. We do not schedule meetings with dogs until an application has been approved. It can take up to a few weeks to process an application or as little time as a few days, from the time you submit an application, please be prepared to adopt as we cannot hold dogs.

Special Requirements

Some dogs may have special requirements (for example, medications, a fence) -- if you apply for a dog, please be sure to read over the biography completely to see if there are any special needs and if you're home would be suitable. If we indicate on the dog's biography that a fence is required, this means your home must have a physical fence. Other dogs may require a "strong vet reference" which indicates that we are looking for a home that has a documented history of veterinary care with previous pets.

The first step in our process is to submit an online adoption application at www.ohiofuzzypawz.com/forms. The application MUST include the personal references and veterinary, grooming, and landlord references (if applicable) and their respective contact information. If you do not include the references and the contact information, your application will be delayed as it CANNOT be processed. Once the references have been successfully completed, a home visit is then scheduled when a rescue representative can meet all members of the family or residents of the home.
No application is approved prior to the home visit being done.
At that point, the Directors will discuss any and all applications on a foster dog and make a selection--in many cases, there are multiple applications for each dog, so please be understanding that our only priority is the successful placement of each of our foster dogs.

Out of State Adoptions

We do adopt out of state to outstanding applicants, however, our process requires a home visit, so out of state adoptions can take longer.
We do not ship our dogs, adopters should be prepared to pick up the dog in Central Ohio.

animal.description:
Looks like: Pitbull Terrier Mix
Male, 8 years old, 62 pounds

Levi is the consummate gentleman. He knows where his people are at all times and likes to be near them but isn't overly invasive and does well left to his own devices. He has been housetrained since setting foot in his foster home and uses the doggie door like an old pro. He has a deep appreciation for food and is usually more interested in seeing if any nearby humans might have treats than in saying hello to other dogs. That said, he has been living seamlessly with a pack of dogs (4 small ones and 1 Pit Bull) in his foster home and enjoys their company. Levi has been infinitely tolerant of the dog-pile mentality of his foster siblings, allowing any or all to share his bed or curl up practically on top of him. 

He is overall a quiet guy but does "talk" when he's feeling especially happy. Levi accepts and offers affection the way he does most everything else - gently and with a grace you wouldn't necessarily expect. He has never met a stranger and "unflappable" seems an apt descriptor. His calm, even temperament and soulful gaze are second to none. 

Levi has done well on pack walks in the redwoods, although he needs shorter adventures for now while he gains back some muscle mass and gets a couple of aches and pains under control. He has been relatively non-reactive to the cats he has seen and reportedly lived with children in a former home (although has aged out of being a physical match for the very young ones). He is simply an incredibly nice dog and an undeniable breed ambassador. 

Levi is from Hollister Animal Services and then was transferred to be fostered with Santa Cruz County Animal Services. He needs some veterinarian attention on his tail so POMDR brought him into our program to have that addressed and get him into a forever home.

Meet Murphy. He's a newly rescued 41 pound lab mix with the cutest short tail that we think is because of his mixed breed. Either way, it really makes his butt wiggle! He's estimated to be 1 year to 1.5 years old and is working on all the puppy training and manners he has missed out on. He's on the skinny side and we are getting some good meals in him. He is enjoying the yard and playing with our bigger resident dog. He is very interested in our small dog who is currently not a fan, so he may do best with medium to bigger dogs. So far, he is doing well with going potty outside. He does not appear to be crate trained. We do not have kids or cats so we are not sure how he would be with them. However, he is definitely enjoying getting some love from his human fosters! Adopt Murphy and give him the love he deserves!

animal.description:
Meet Christian! He's looking for his special home! 

Hi I'm Christian but my foster family calls me Maui, like from Moana! I'm a French Bulldog and 5 years old! My foster family isn't sure what happened but I had an accident before Saving Hope saved me! I have several ruptured discs in my spine and slowly my back legs have just stopped doing what I want them to do. I'm a wobbly boy but I have the biggest personality! I love to play but can be a little snippy so it would probably be best to live in a home with no or older kids and with a non dominant dog or as an only fur child! I like to chase cats so probably no kitty siblings either! Because of my spinal injury, I'm having a little trouble waiting to get outside to go potty but with a consistent schedule I can try my hardest! My foster parents take such good care of me that I try to be the best guard dog ever! Sometimes I can get upset with new people coming in my home so I need slow introductions. 

No stairs/steps, no kids, no cats, probably only dog unless they're submissive, he is very protective of his home/people and will get aggressive. It's mainly right when someone walks in the door or up to the car. He plays rough and nippy but is full of love and just wants to cuddle all day. He goes INSANE for any type of ball and loves to sun bathe. He is starting to really lose his control of going to the bathroom. He will pee when excited, when or after he eats and he's been pooping himself awake in the mornings poor thing.

Tanzi is a 3 year old Boxer Lab mix (best guess). She has a short, red coat with white toes and chest. She weighs in at 80 pounds and stands 24 inches at the shoulder. Yes, she needs to lose a few pounds. She was brought to the shelter because her owner had to go into an assisted living facility. She is very well mannered, walks nicely on leash, knows sit, down, shake, and come.  Tanzi does well at the dog park with other dogs. She initially plays but due to her being overweight, she tires easily and then goes off and does her own thing.  Tanzi lived with two indoor cats. Initially she wasn't fond of them but adjusted to them and eventually ignored them. Tanzi is friendly with people of all ages. The neighbor kids used to play with her in the yard. She enjoys playing fetch and will bring it back for you to throw again. Tanzi is an easy going gal that will make a great family dog in town or in the country. She will need regular exercise to get her to a healthy weight.

animal.description:
Mix: Mixed

Age/DOB: 3 Years  

Vaccines:  UTD

Microchip:  Yes

House trained: Yes

Crate trained: Yes

Spayed/ Neutered: Yes

Bio: ? 

Freckles is estimated to be 3 years of age, she is spayed, housebroken and utd on all vaccines and preventives. She does very well making friends outside of the home but masks do scare this girl so in certain times it takes her a few to understand not seeing someone's facial expressions. She is still a happy go lucky girl that loves to please the people she attaches herself too.. She knows sit and learning more commands. Freckles has settled into her foster home but does guard her space to new people. She likes her space and not having too many people in her sleeping*(safe) area or up in her face. Best way to explain this behavior is Freckles lived in Boarding for 2 years of her life and now in a home her mind believes the Kennel is her home. She becomes protective of what is considered her space. We are working with this behavior by opening up more of the home to Freckles slowly but it takes time to correct.  Freckles is also being worked with in meeting people in her new home and that it is a good thing. Outside the home she will meet everyone perfectly with her handlers. People that she has entrusted her self too that will protect her.  Freckles would love a forever and deserves a quite home that understands her personality.  She would do best in a home with another dog her size and preferably a male as she doesn't like to be alone for too long and misses having a furry friend. During her time she has been enjoying daily hiking trips and exploring beautiful Hunterdon County. When back at home she is pretty low key and just soaks up being cozy and warm. She does very well on a leash but those pesky squirrels like to pull her attention sometimes so she is learning to leave it. Freckles will need a home with no children under the age of 18 and no potential grandchildren that the family will not be able to put her away while visiting. If you are interested in fostering or adopting this girl. Please message us or complete an application at our website at www.njmisfitsk9rescue.com

Characteristics

This is Banks. We rescued Banks and his sister, Ivy in the middle of January. They were roaming around in Cordova, SC and were kindly taken in by a local resident! We went and picked them up and they could not be any more adorable!

Banks loves people and other dogs! Banks is a year old, he is a terrier mix, he is also up-to-date on all of his shots and is neutered. Banks is shy and a little more skeptical of things more than his sister is. Banks likes to "be in the know" and like to be in the middle of everything! He has one eye that is a light blue color and the other is a very pretty golden brown! 

Banks is a very loving, caring, and sweet dog! He is more on the higher energy level and is more playful than his sister! Banks loves his sister Ivy a lot! They both love each other dearly!

Please consider Banks when looking for your next family member and companion!

animal.description:
Sweet Pea has just about the best personality you could ask for. She is calm, laid back and happy to lucky. She is good with dogs, cats and loves children. 

Sweet Pea came to us from Texas after needing rescue due to a leg injury. We were told her leg got caught in a hog trap by the owner, the vet in Texas believes she was used as hog bait- not an uncommon thing apparently. She also had a few lacerations and were stitched and have now healed. There’s more to her story, she also came with 6 underweight tiny babies that were infested with worms and fleas. Sweet Pea herself wasn’t extremely emaciated. During her vet visit we learned she was also heartworm positive. The good news is heartworm is very treatable and now that she has put weight on we have begun her heartworm treatment. Anyone who is interested in sweet pea will need to bring her back to us one last time so we can take her to the vets for her final injection. She will also be required to limit any heavy activity ( not a big worry, sweet pea is a lazy girl anyhow). We know Sweet Pea is a great dog, we will be looking for someone special to adopt her. Will that be you?

animal.description: Joker was dumped in a shelter in South Carolina because he was left outside and wandered off (even though there was no fence to keep him home). Now that he's living inside a home and many other dogs, he has enjoyed becoming part of a family for the first time in his five years. Joker is about 5 years old.  He is submissive and very, very sweet.  He's a cuddler! When he comes to you, nose is down as beagles will do. Joker is a low rider and weighs 27 lbs. He has been with children, men and women and likes them all.  He gets along great with the other dogs and seems to like to be with the other small fosters in the house.  Joker is getting better with house breaking and with a little work, should be there in no time.  Joker's new family should have experience with Beagles.  If you think Joker is the boy you've been waiting for, your first step is to copy and paste this link to your web browser to fill out our online application, https://www.jotform.com/form/200215767055148.  Joker is now up to date on vaccines, neutered, heart worm negative and microchipped, included in his $475 adoption fee. Transport up north from South Carolina is an additional $125. We cannot be certain what his true mix is.

animal.description:
1/13/21 Zoey came to STAF when her family moved and was unable to take her along. Zoey is almost three years old (born 4/18/18) and is reportedly house-trained, crate-trained and not a chewer. We can vouch that she is a real lover. We're working on her leash manners (she tends to pull every which way) and her weight. (No judging ... we've all put on some pandemic pounds.) Poor girl arrived with an ear infection and some skin issues that we are working to resolve. Please check back for updates as we get to know Zoe better. Visit STAF.org for more information on our adoption process.

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions. You will be asked to return for at least one follow-up visit, then take the dog home for a trial period before officially adopting. 
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we can not adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.

animal.description:
MEET AVALON!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4510510.

Avalon has been at the shelter for over 30 days and the stress of the shelter environment is beginning to take its toll on him. Avalon has been observed chewing on the bars of his kennel and licking the concrete walls which means he can't take much more of being in a kennel. When volunteers have taken Avalon for a walk, they have reported that he pulls hard on the leash to get out which is understandable since he's so happy to GO!! But once he gets out of the shelter, he calms down and walks great on a leash. He is very affectionate and gentle and will lean in so that he can get as many pets as he can. He loves his treats and takes them gently. When his walk ends and he comes back to the shelter, he goes into his kennel easily.

Avalon is picky about his canine friends and would probably do better in a home as the only dog. However, he may be okay with another dog if he found his perfect friend. He needs a dog introduction if an adopter already has a dog at home. Avalon cannot live with cats or any other small animals and any children in the home should be more than 12 years old. If you think Avalon would be a good fit in your home, please come and meet this handsome, affectionate guy today!! He would love to go home soon.

If you are interested in saving this pet, please reach out via this link: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

To actually visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

PLEASE READ AS THE CLINICS ARE NOT OPEN TO THE PUBLIC: . The clinics where our animals are housed are currently not open for viewing animals due to the quarantine. Since we can't meet you in person currently, if you are interested in meeting this pet, please email information about yourself, family, residence and current/prior pet experience. If it is a good fit you will be sent an application. Once that is approved, arrangements will be made for you to see the pet. Thanks for your understanding!


Rocky Road is a sweet and playful Catahoula Leopard Dog mix who is about 1 year old and looking for his forever home. We have only had Rocky Road for a short time, but we do know that he seems to do well with everyone he meets including other dogs thus far. He was originally rescued from a shelter in Kentucky when his time was up and we have little information about his history prior to coming to us. Rocky Road's adoption fee is $299 and includes his neuter, microchip, vaccinations and routine labwork. Please email us if interested in adopting.

Their Adoption Process
1. Submit Application
2. Approve Application
3. Meet the Pet
Additional Adoption Info
• Must be 21 years of age or older to adopt a cat, 23 years of age or older to adopt a dog.

• Must provide a copy of your lease agreement or association by laws if you live in an apartment, condo or townhouse

• Must provide documents/receipts that specify your cat or dog’s immunizations/required tests are current (rabies, distemper and fecal (+ for dogs- heartworm test and bordetella if adopting a dog) (+ for cats - leukemia test/vaccine if adopting a cat)). We can call your veterinarian to get this information, if you don’t have the documents.

• All adults in the household must be present and co sign the adoption agreement.

• All your currently owned dogs/cats must be spayed or neutered. This is a non-negotiable requirement.

• Heartworm prevention for dogs must also be purchased at the time of adoption and prices vary depending on the size of the animal being adopted.

• Puppies under 6 months old are required to sign up for a puppy obedience class. ($89 deposit required, refundable upon completion)

Each Adoption Includes:
• Spay or neuter surgery
Vaccines current to the date of adoption *:
• Rabies vaccine
• Bordatella vaccine for dogs
• Canine Influenza vaccine for dogs
• Booster for canine and feline distemper and several other dangerous diseases
• Fecal test
• 1st deworming
• Heartworm test (dogs +6 months old)
• Leukemia test for cats
• Capstar flea treatment
• Microchip identification implant
* Boosters required for puppies and kittens (depending on age) POST adoption are the responsibility of the pet owner.

Application Process

Once you have decided on an animal, you will be provided with an Adoption Questionnaire which requires name, address, phone numbers and asks some questions about your household, why you want a pet and how you plan to care for it. The Adoption Questionnaire needs to be approved by an authorized humane society volunteer. If an authorized volunteer is on site, that occurs quickly and if you’ve provided all required information on applicable lease agreements/association by laws and current immunizations/tests for any existing pets, you may be able to take your new friend home immediately. If an authorized volunteer is not on site, you’ll receive a phone call or email when the status is determined.

Adopotion Donations

Adoption donations for adult dogs range from $59 to $399 and puppies from $159 to $599.
Adoption donations for adult cats range from $29 to $99 and kittens from $59 to $399.


We are a private pet rescue and are not affiliated with any government or national organization, and as such our adoption donations are set to cover as much of the cost for the spay/neuter surgery, vaccinations, tests and medical care of our animals that is realistic. We lose money on every animal we take in as our adoption donations are less than what caring for the animals actually costs us. We ask more for puppies, kittens and purebred adults to help cover the expenses of the older mixed breed animals for which we receive minimal donations and incur significant debt. However, even at our highest prices, puppies and kittens are still half the price of pet store animals AND our animals are already altered and up to date on vaccinations.

Post Adoption Care

If you choose to give one of our deserving homeless animals a second chance at a good life, a New Pet Health Assurance Program provided by our partner veterinary clinics is available. This will cover the cost of treating shelter related illnesses should one occur, for 60 days after your adoption date up to $500. If you do not purchase this coverage, you would assume total financial responsibility for any needed medical treatment immediately after you adopt.

Help Save Pets

Since 2000, we have placed over 10,000 animals into loving homes. Each one of these animals was given shelter, food, medical aid and vaccinations and time to find the right home. Our doctors mended mutilated limbs and cured many illnesses so that these animals could get a second chance at good lives. We have grown and now operate out of 4 locations, not all of them in Plainfield. In 2008 we changed our name from the Humane Society of Plainfield to Help Save Pets, still HSP.


What exactly does HSP do?
We rescue desirable and healthy adult dogs and cats from pounds and shelters in mostly rural areas.

• Many government funded pounds and shelters, especially in rural areas, have an abundance of homeless animals and scarce cage space to house them. The demand for pets from these shelters is low and the kill rate is high.

We rescue puppies and kittens that most rescues will not.
• Many shelters, including other no kill rescues, will NOT take puppies or kittens under 3 months old because of their susceptibility to illness. Most are sadly put to death.

We rescue dogs and cats with curable health problems.
• Many adult animals with curable health problems (some serious, including Heartworm positive dogs) are restored to health and offered for adoption.

We take pregnant and nursing moms with their babies.
• We find foster homes for them to raise their young in a safe environment. Pounds put these moms and their babies down immediately because of the risk of illness, extra work and additional space involved with caring for them.

We work closely with Will County and Joliet Township Animal Control to help reduce the kill rate of animals locally.

We sponsor an Illinois Dept of Agriculture Humane Investigator, who serves our geographic area and investigates cruelty complaints.

We offer training and behavioral counseling to assist in the transition of adopted animals into new homes.

Go Meet Their Pets
Email inquires can be directed to availablepets@gmail.com

More About This Rescue
Help Save Pets is a humane society that has locations in Channahon, Downers Grove, Hinsdale, Oswego, and Shorewood, Chicago (Old Town) Illinois and Gahanna and Lewis Center Ohio







Adoption donations for adult dogs range from $59 to $299 and puppies from $159 to $599. This includes:
- Spay or neuter surgery
Vaccines current to the date of adoption*:
- Rabies vaccine
- Booster for feline Distemper, Rhinotracheitis, Calicivirus and Chlamydia (DRCC)
- Fecal test
- 1st worming
- Feline Leukemia test
- Capstar flea treatment
- Microchip identification implant
* Boosters required for puppies and kittens (depending on age) POST adoption are the responsibility of the pet owner.
. Puppies under 6 months old are required to sign up for a puppy obedience class. ($89 deposit required, refundable upon completion)

Come Ready to Adopt: 
If you rent or live in a condo/townhouse with an association, bring your lease/bylaws indicating pets are allowed and if there are any restrictions. We require vaccinations and tests to be up to date for the protection of your current pets. Bringing their vet records can help speed the adoption

animal.description:
1/13/21 Rani and her big (if only by a few pounds) Regal were bought as pups ... but once they got "too big" they were tied up outside for several months. It was a cold day in January when they they got a warm room at STAF--and an even warmer greeting from our volunteers. They may need a refresher course on house manners, but are quickly remembering the comforts of being "indoor dogs," complete with soft blankets and human snuggles. Rani weighs right around 50 pounds and is about 10 month old. (Est. birth date March 2019.) Her breed-mix is a mystery--shepherd/collie is our best guess at this point. Please check back for updates as we get to know her better. Visit STAF.org for more information on our adoption process.

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions. You will be asked to return for at least one follow-up visit, then take the dog home for a trial period before officially adopting. 
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we can not adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.

animal.description:
Sometimes you just don't know what you are going to find when you open one of 500 emails that you receive in a day's time, merely because you are a rescue group. Critter Cavalry answered an email of desperation back almost 2 months ago and saw this precious boy's face. The owner of this young 10 month old pup (a Bulldog mixed with something intriguing) said that he had some neurological/genetic defects that made him walk funny and sometimes a little unpredictable when you try to redirect behavior. This boy has a very common form of Hydrocephalus that we are told is common in the Bulldog breeds. He was born this way. Lucky Chance is his name and we promised him that we would find the perfect family that would understand and Forgive his imperfections. This boy is always going to have his physical challenges and some of his mood triggers that a special needs sensitive family can work with. He has been raised until 2 months ago With little or no real guidance. He is good with other dogs and loves people but sometimes he is a little reactive when you try to redirect his behavior or what he is doing. I guess we could say that sometimes He is mentally challenged too and you just love him through it. His foster mom has seen improvement in the past two months and we are so hopeful that this 50 pound boy with the serious look (but is honestly Goofy) will be scooped up by a loving family that understands the compassion that Lucky Chance deserves. If you are interested please email us at ccrtennessee@gmail.com

ADOPTION FEE REQUIRED. Contact ccrtennessee@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Hello everyone! My name is Baabs I’m an approximately 8 month 30 pound little lady. I love people! My pastimes include snuggling, long naps, walks, and of course playtime with my foster family. I am very playful love to play chase and tug of war. Fetch is fun too but a little confusing for me. I prefer catch and play with the toy as opposed to returning it. I am a good girl, and am learning basic commands like sit. I’m also fully potty trained. My foster mom says I’m going to make the best dog for a lucky family I’m very tolerant and good with kids. I will need a family who is patient with me and can continue to help me grow and be a great dog. I am still a puppy and can get excited and a little mouthy and need some redirection with my toys. I LOVE my toys especially chew toys. A fenced yard and an active family with time to play and work with on some basic skills would be a good match for me. So who is ready for some puppy snuggles and licks?

The adoptive family should have older kids only (10+) and a fully fenced in yard. Having another dog in the family is highly encouraged! Baabs would probably do well with a larger male dog with equal energy.

The adoption fee of $300.00 will include spay/neuter, microchip, age appropriate/required vaccinations, treatment for heartworm and any other necessary medical treatment to assure a healthy new pup for your family.


IMPORTANT DISCLAIMER: Although we do our best to describe breed, since our pups all come from shelters we can not and will not make any guarantee on breed or size. We can tell you that they are 100% RESCUED! And that is the BEST breed!

If you are interested in adopting/meeting , please visit our website at www.starfishanimalrescue.com or you may complete the online adoption application on our Facebook Page https://www.facebook.com/starfishanimalrescue/app/134425496630143/?ref=page_internal Once you complete and submit your dog adoption application we will set up an appointment to meet this pup!

*please note that we are a foster home based rescue and we do home visits as part of the adoption process - we are unable to adopt to families who live outside of the Chicago and surrounding suburbs. Thank you for your understanding.

Timid Teddy is a 1 to 2 year-old male beagle who recently arrived on the freedom ride from North Carolina to New Jersey. He was rescued from horrific living conditions in North Carolina by our wonderful southern volunteers. 

Teddy is up to date on vaccinations and heartworm negative. Due to the urgency of the situation he has not been neutered.

animal.description:
Because we are all volunteers, Illinois Doberman Rescue Plus only considers approved applicants to meet our orphans in our foster homes. Please read our eligibility requirements and apply on our website: www.ildoberescue.com/adopt.  After an application is submitted, additional inquiries can email dobes@ildoberescue.com.

Maximillian hopes the third time is the charm because his first two placements were not the right fit. He was initially surrendered to another organization at 8 months old with no history, and the nice family that adopted him didn’t realize how much work a Doberman puppy would be with two young kids already. They worked with a trainer, who suggested rehoming him through IDR+ since we have a wonderful pool of adopters with previous Doberman experience who attend positive reinforcement training. Maximillian is now just over a year old, and he is a puppy brain in a 95 lb body. In the previous home, he took treats nicely, but he did not appreciate the energy, noise, and attention of young kids. Homes with teens that can be involved in consistent positive training can be considered. Older folks who don’t appreciate getting jumped on are also not a good fit. His previous home had an elderly cat who kept her distance, but he seemed too focused when he’d see her, so we aren’t comfortable placing him with a cat. Maximillian would also appreciate being the only dog in the home. In his foster home, he can co-exist with x-pens and baby gates keeping everyone separated, but he lacks appropriate social skills to be loose with dogs. He comes on too strong, which is triggering for many dogs. He is not a candidate for a dog park.

Maximillian has some anxiety, which sadly is more and more common in the breed, and our vet put him on a very inexpensive but effective anti-anxiety medication to help him cope. He will need to continue this medication for life. He still struggles with calmly riding in the car, so his adoption range is limited to within an hour of the Chicagoland area to minimize the stress of yet another placement. Maximilian will require a commitment to positive training, and he would appreciate private in-home classes so he can focus on learning. We can provide recommendations. He understands a few basic commands, but he needs more advanced attention to get him on the right track. He is treat-motivated, so he should succeed in the right hands.

In his foster home, Maximilian has a lot of energy and loves to play, run, and get the zoomies. His foster dad admits that can be wild at times and bounce off the walls, but he does settle down.  Like most Dobermans, Maximillian loves attention and always wants needs a ‘job’ to stimulate his mind and body. He loves to play ‘find it.’ He is crate trained and does not mind being in a crate while no one is home, but he would rather be with his foster dad when he’s home instead of in his crate. He will contribute to work calls with his Doberman sounds. In his previous home, Maximillian got stressed when the neighbor dog barked at him through the fence, so he will require a 6-foot privacy fenced yard (no e-fence) to minimize previous issues. He also needs help to walk nicely on a leash, so don’t plan on taking him for long walks quite yet. He is housebroken, but he needs extra potty breaks if he’s stressed. We know this is a lot of information and high expectations, but Maximillian needs his next home to be his forever home.

The biographical information provided is correct to the best of our knowledge while the animal is in our care or includes what may have been provided by a previous owner. We strive to be honest and accurate, but animals can change their personalities and behavior when they settle into a new home. IDR+ makes no guarantees based on the information we observe and provide.

animal.description:
Hi, we are Gus and Woody, or more formally known as Augustus and Woodrow.  Our former owner loved us very much but sadly passed away.  Several other family members tried to take us in but none had the right set up to welcome two additional dogs.  So we have traveled from Texas to Wisconsin to get our new start.  We are very much a bonded pair and need to stay together, although we do sometimes like a little space from each other.  We have been through a lot and it would be a much easier transition for us to go to a home where we would be the only dogs.  We were fostered with a cat in Texas without issue.  Older kids in the home would be just fine but we can be a bit jumpy for little ones.

     Let us tell you more about our lives currently.  Woody gets up early at about 5:00, for a bathroom break, then settles back in bed for a couple hours.  Gus likes to sleep until 7:30.  We fill the morning with outside play and chase with each other and our two furry foster brothers.  We eat breakfast at about 8:30 and eat separately so everyone gets their fair share-no stealing.  After breakfast we go outside again for more play and exploring. We chase squirrels and once a bunny.  We follow that up with a morning nap for about an hour.

     When we get up, if foster mom plays her ukulele, Gus loves to start an all-out howl fest.  He is the best howler amongst us!  He also loves to watch out the window for his friend Daisy to go by. She is a cute beagle that lives
down the street. and he loves her.  About this time we all go for a 30 minute walk in the neighborhood.  We love to sniff all the smells.  We get to see other dogs and our neighbor's little boys. We greet them with a wagging tail but have to be held back because we want to jump up with excitement.  We usually go on two walks a day so we recognize the kids and dogs on our route.

     At home we snuggle and chew Nylabones, and play indoors until the next potty break.  If we see neighbor Al, we cry for him to bring us a treat.  We generally nap some more, walk again, and eat dinner at 4:00pm.  By then we are pretty beat so we do some couch lounging and alternate between dog beds.  We take a few more evening potty breaks, then lights out at 10:00 pm.  We settle in pretty quickly with our pillows and blankets.  Woody likes to sleep together, though Gus can get grumbly about sharing.

Notes from foster mom:
     Woody loves belly rubs and hugs, snuggling, running and playing.  He loves to eat and loves Gus.  He is sweet and funny and happy-go-lucky much of the time.  He whines when he needs to go outside for a bathroom break.  Woody can get cranky trying to adjust to new experiences but tries to adjust to the pack. 
     Gus loves all the things Woody loves.  He needs to go straight out potty when he wakes from a nap so he doesn't have an accident as he did the first few days here.  Sometimes he does a little snarl if he gets startled awake, until he sees he is ok.  Otherwise he is a pretty cool little dude that is not really afraid of anything.
     Neither dog has any specific training needs and they are not needing to be crated.  They are living with two furry foster brothers and do like to play together but needed to be heavily monitored initially while getting to know one another.  They wrestle and chase squirrels and romp in the snow or get in the compost together.  They need a family with a lot of time for them.  They previously did not have that and Woody gets particularly upset about being left.  He needs to find a home that gives him security and stability.  They are good on leashes when out walking and good in the car, but Woody doesn't enjoy the vet visits.

If you have room in your heart and home for two great new additions, please fill out the application under the Adoption heading on our website www.bassetbuddiesrescue.org and a volunteer will reach out to you.

animal.description:
Honey bun came to us The ninth of January. She is 8 years old. I immediately noticed she had severe separation anxiety. Thankfully with all that I have going on, Chanel stepped up to foster her. She g
Honey bun came to us The ninth of January. She is 8 years old. I immediately noticed she had severe separation anxiety. Thankfully with all that I have going on, Chanel stepped up to foster her. She goes into such a panic that she harms herself trying to escape. We even think she has a couple broken teeth as a result. She will get a dental in a couple weeks. For now she is on a soft food diet. Part of that may be she's spoiled and finicky, but she is still on the thin side. She is 13 pounds. She looks a lot smaller in person. She is a Chiweenie. She does not like to be outside. Her behavior is odd. She sort of looks to the sky and seems confused. Her head bobs left and right, like she's not sure where to go and she whines. We hope that will get better as she gets more confident. She is not interested in other dogs, but worships her new foster Mom. Chanel keeps her close trying to keep her calm. She even has a sling she caries around for her. She has been vetted except for the dental, so she can be placed in a forever home. Chanel says she's very much like caring for a baby. She's extremely sweet and loves to cuddle and give kisses. Applicants absolutely must be at home more than the majority of time. We hope she finds the perfect person. We don't have a history on her but it's hard to imagine this sweet thing ended up in a shelter in Texas. She really deserves the love and kindness of a new home. Apply at
www.misfitsdogrescue.org
Her adoption fee is $150.

animal.description:
**DO NOT EMAIL ASKING IF. A PUPPY/DOG IS STILL AVAILABLE. if a puppy/dog is still listed, then we are still accepting applications**

*Name: Marine

*Age: approximately 2 years old

*Weight: 51 pounds

*Health: Up to date on vaccines, Neutered, & microchipped

*Requirements: Physically Fully Fenced & secured yard, no cats.

ABOUT MARINE:
He is curious, independent and adventure-seeking. He does enjoy attention and will roll over for belly rubs. Marine loves other dogs and seeks them out to play. He would love a buddy to run and exercise some of his energy out with. He absolutely loves water, and would love the opportunity to splash around in a shallow pool or shallow pond. Because he is a higher energy dog so a home with a fully fenced in yard. 

He LOVES to play and run, he would be happiest in an active outdoor-oriented family who will allow him time to exercise. He does well in a crate, and is house trained. He is food motivated, so treats capture his attention and he is quick to comply for treats. He is currently working with a trainer for his manners and is doing very well. He is being E-Collar trained so a home with experience on this is preferred. Marine is currently in foster located in Cape Cod, MA.

Marine is also Heartworm positive, Good news is that we caught it early, He has gone through the required treatment and is getting his monthly Heartworm preventative. He is doing great and never let it slow him down.


Marine's adoption fee is $375.00
Applications for adoption can be found at https://snarrapps.org/adopt-app/
If you fill out an application, please make sure you answer all the questions in as much detail as possible and that you receive a confirmation email, otherwise we did NOT receive it.

---------*Important FAQ’s*———————

- Please understand that we are a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers try to answer all emails/questions as quickly as possible, below please find answers to some of our most frequently asked questions. We ask that you please read the FAQ's to see if your questions have already been answered before emailing additional questions:

-If a dog or puppy is listed on Petfinder, they are still available. Please do not email asking if they are still available. If a dog or puppy is still listed, then we are accepting applications :) We do not go on a first come first serve basis, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.

-We are taking our best guess on breed and size when fully grown (or already an adult), based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. We rarely are able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time.

**This is a Courtesy Listing for a dog available for adoption at The Animal Pad, a rescue based in San Diego. Please use contact information below for inquiries.**

Meet Windansea!

Windansea was rescued from the streets of Tijuana in and was terribly skinny when he arrived. He is approximately 6-7 years old and weighs 70 lbs. We suspect Windan sea may have been hit by a car at one point, as he has some arthritis in his hips, but he moves well and enjoys walks and activity.

Windansea has been at The Animal Pad since August 2020, but he keeps getting overlooked by potential adopters. They are missing out on a very sweet and mellow guy! He's great with people and would probably be happiest as an only dog. Windansea can be a bit reactive toward other dogs on leash, but he is redirected easily! He is very eager to please, and like the boxer we think he partly is, Windansea is "chatty" with moans and whines when he's excited, very food motivated, and LOVES to lean in for pets and attention!

Windansea has come a long way from the emaciated dog he was when he first came to The Animal Pad. He's ready for his Forever Family!

If you’d like to apply to adopt, please submit an application using the link below.
Application link (please copy and paste into your browser's address bar)
https://ws.ishelters.com/application.php?k=coonhOUnd&t=Beagle%20Adoption

About our rescue
We are a foster based rescue. Our dogs are in foster homes throughout the area or in some cases in the south waiting to be transported north. We do not have a physical shelter. However, meet and greets are set up for approved applicants.

Our Adoption Process
Visit our website www.necoonhoundrescue.org for information about the Coonhound and Beagle breeds. Read ‘Is a Coonhound Right for You’. 
If you'd like to apply, our application is available at the link above. Once we review your application one of our Adoption Counselors will be in touch to review it with you. Once the phone interview is completed, we will check your vet reference as well as a personal reference and conduct a home visit.

animal.description:
SPECIAL NEEDS

Allow me to introduce you to Chloe AKA Chloe the Magnificent! Chloe is a blind and deaf female cattle dog mix. She’s currently about 9 lbs and 11 weeks old. Although Chloe experiences the world differently, she still does your average puppy things. She absolutely loves to be pet and have her tummy rubbed. When you first pick her up, be patient as she will wiggle around nervously until she recognizes your scent. She loves to pounce around, steal shoes to chew on and get in the mix with her Forster siblings. Because she is unaware of her surroundings at times, she may howl and cry a bit until she figures out where she is and feels safe. In fairness to Chloe, TRAINING IS A MUST.  Safety is of the utmost importance. Signs, signals and tricks of the trade you may have used with pets in the past may not work for Chloe. She will need specific and consistent training to fit her needs. Once Chloe warms up and is familiar with your scent, she will want to be by your side whenever possible, so a stay at home caregiver may be best. ONLY IF  you are willing to put the time in to join Chloe in how she sees the world, fill out an application at Louieslegacy.org and you will not be disappointed in the love and friendship she has to offer in return.  COMMITTED APPLICANTS ONLY!!

This pet's adoption fee is $500. She is being fostered in Staten Island
