animal.description:
Larson is a 5 year old Shepherd/Labrador Retriever/Cattle Dog mix weighing 50 lbs. No, he’s not a senior, but we were originally told he was 7-8 so we took a chance on him. Whoopsies. Larson came to us from Northern Arizona where he was potentially used as a bait dog. Poor guy. He had over 100+ bite wounds all over him on his legs, head, ears, tail, and etc. Larson is all healed up physically now and ready for a forever home.  


Larson is currently in a foster home and his personality comes through as he continues to gain confidence and learns to trust his foster family and furry foster brothers/sisters. He enjoys eating on a schedule and it seemed to help him relax knowing he isn't going to starve like before.  Larson is a good walker on the leash and enjoys daily exercise. He is great with his 3 foster siblings that include 2 female labs and a large male Husky.  Larson has not been tested with cats.  He loves loves loves attention and would do best in a home that has someone there with him a good bit of the time. Even a companion pup would be even better. Through continued positive reinforcement training and love Larson will make an awesome addition to any family lucky to be the ones to give him his forever home.    


Do you have room in your heart and home for Larson?

animal.description:
**WE ARE ALWAYS IN NEED OF FOSTER HOMES**  Homeward Bound Dog Rescue is an all volunteer rescue organization and all our dogs and puppies are in foster homes - we are not a shelter and do NOT have a facility where we house our dogs. For adoption information go to: www.homewardbounddogrescue.com.  You must fill out an application online as we do NOT accept applications at our clinics.

Hi. I am Joey, a 12-year-old Dachshund/Beagle mix, but I am young at heart. My favorite parts of the day are running outside and eating. A slow feeder bowl is nice for me, but not a requirement.  I am quiet most of the time until my beagle nose smells food!  I am also extremely visually impaired. It takes me a couple weeks to learn the floor plan of a home. Until I am comfortable, I do like to hug the wall when walking.  I am much more comfortable on a rug then on bare floors because I have a bit of a wobble in my walk and my balance isn't great.  This could be due to some spinal decompression, but at any rate, it  helps me to have something to grip with my feet.  When I am outside though, you would never know there is a problem.  I love to run and play. Bright natural light is great for my vision. I can be very stubborn on a leash. I have done very well around dogs and cats, but I do a lot of growling though. I know they are close, but due to my poor vision, I cannot see what or who is near me.  I do growl a lot when other animals get close to my food bowl, but I have never done more than growl. I have not met any children to know if I like them. I had to have all of my teeth removed so I eat soft food.  I am a great little cuddler, and really enjoy belly rubs.  The most impressive thing about me is how perfectly potty trained I am. I have not had a single accident and have not damaged anything in the house.  I am a perfect boy and deserve a great home.
 

We are presently not holding our regular Saturday adoption clinics due to the Covid-19 virus.  We are operating on a limited basis until further notice, but we are still adopting dogs out. We require an approved application before we consider anyone for an adoption - so filling out the application is your first step.   Different dogs and puppies go up for adoption EVERY WEEK so please feel free to visit the site and click on the Petfinder link for updates. Puppies and dogs up to 2 years old are $350. Dogs over 2 years old are $250. 100% of the adoption fees go to help us save more dogs.
animal.name: Joey

animal.description:
This is Bruce aka Batman. He survived pneumonia and is being potty and leashed trained. Bruce has quite the personality, loves playing and cuddling. He is all legs and is still trying to run smoothly on them. Clumsy little guy! One of his favorite things to do is play ball. He will bat the ball around with his feet, then pick it up and throw it and then repeat. With training he could really learn how to play ball well. He also plays well with all his litter mates and enjoys playing tug o war. He wants to be in the middle of everything. And then he will just cuddle with you and settle his head on your shoulder. It is important that the adopter of Bruce be VERY active as this boy will need a lot of activity throughout his day to get his energy out and remain healthy and happy.

animal.description:
Meet Costello!!

He came to us after healing from a gunshot wound, so he is learning to trust people again and his foster mom is doing a wonderful job teaching him that he is loved and safe! He is a love bug and is doing ok integrating with his foster siblings. We don't think he was socialized before he came to us, so it's been a process getting him to relax with the other dogs. He does great on pack walks and is learning that other dogs are ok! He is a professional napper and he loves to squeeze under his foster mom's little table to nap! He is very food motivated so that makes training much easier. He recently met some friends of his foster mom's and he did really good (snacks help!). 

This boy is a bit rough around the edges, but he is truly a diamond in the rough! Once he figures out that he can trust you, you will have a friend for life! Come meet him and never spend another night alone!

 

If you are interested in adopting, please visit our website and complete an adoption application at www.elpasocountycanine.org/adopt

animal.description:
Scooby is a friendly, 7 year old beagle who was surrendered by a local family for severe separation anxiety. Scooby has had a rough time. He was adopted from a shelter in Florida about a year ago. He was surrendered to the shelter with another dog he was bonded to because the family was moving. Unfortunately, the shelter separated the two and adopted Scooby out as an only dog. Over the course of the year,  Scooby became increasingly stressed and vocal being left alone and his family asked for help rehoming him. 

Scooby is a hefty boy, weighing in at about 45 lbs. The best home for him is a home with at least two humans and another dog with the same energy level as Scooby is active and likes to play. When he is bored he will get into things, but has been going to daycare while at his foster home and has had no issues getting into things at home. He walks well on a leash with a harness. He is house trained, sleeps in bed with his fosters and is practicing being left alone for short periods of time. He is very food motivated and like all beagles, will steal food if given the opportunity. Scooby is being fostered in Massachusetts and is available for visits with approved adopters. 

If you’d like to apply to adopt, please submit an application using the link below.
Application link (please copy and paste into your browser's address bar)
https://ws.ishelters.com/application.php?k=coonhOUnd&t=Beagle%20Adoption

About our rescue
We are a foster based rescue. Our dogs are in foster homes throughout the area or in some cases in the south waiting to be transported north. We do not have a physical shelter. However, meet and greets are set up for approved applicants.

Our Adoption Process
Visit our website www.necoonhoundrescue.org for information about the Coonhound and Beagle breeds. Read ‘Is a Coonhound Right for You’. 
If you'd like to apply, our application is available at the link above. Once we review your application one of our Adoption Counselors will be in touch to review it with you. Once the phone interview is completed, we will check your vet reference as well as a personal reference and conduct a home visit.

Spock earned his name from his very expressive ears, which fold over or perk up to show if he's feeling curious or playful. He is 4 yrs old, weighs 41lbs and has the build of a fox terrier/large JRT. Spock is an active guy who loves to zoom and play with his doggie and human pals and he can outrun just about everyone! He's outgoing and happy-go-lucky.

If you are interested in any of our dogs, please complete our online adoption application:

http://www.lifesaverssp.dreamhosters.com/adoption-applicat
/

We will conduct a phone interview, check references and then a home check. This helps us to match a dog with their potential adopter. The adoption fee is $350.00 for adults and $450.00 for puppies under one year which includes spay/neutering, up-to-date age appropriate vaccinations, flea/tick & heartworm preventative and a health certificate. We foster our dogs in homes, not in shelters. This allows us to get to know the dogs temperaments in order to match them to a home. This also allows us to get the dogs ready to live in their forever homes! All dogs coming from the south have been quarantined for two weeks and fully vetted before traveling to New England!

For more info please email Lifesaversapps@outlook.com OR visit our website:

http://www.lifesaverssp.org/

animal.description:
Aries is a beautiful, approximately 70lb, 2.5 year old Dutch Shepherd Mix looking for a stable, loving home to call her own. Aries is well behaved thrives in a home environment whereby she is provided routine and structure. 

While she enjoys the occasional short car ride and new experience, Aries loves her time at home the most; her people and a snuggly bed are most important to her. Aries gets along well with other dogs and would love a furry friend to play with! Please keep in mind however that her play style (due to her size) is best suited with dogs of at least medium size or larger (she currently resides wiht a Jack Russell, but her size is best suited for larger play friends). Aries easily recognizes that kongs, bones, and hard toys that are designated for her oral exercise while avoiding chewing on items that are prohibited. Aries has done well with children, but her size might also make her a better candidate for a home without very small children. Aries is house trained, knows how to use a doggy door, and easily masters simple commands such as sit, stay, wait, etc. Aries is a quick learner and motivated by treats, including ice cubes! 

If you're looking for a new best friend to join you in your daily routines and quickly become your #1 fan, apply today to meet Aries! 

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

animal.description:
Meet Terra! Shes fiercely independent and very confident in all situations. She likes to start all her play wrestling matches, even with the adult Great Dane in her foster home! Shes curious and loves to explore; being outside is her favorite because shes got so much energy. Shes very very intelligent almost to a fault and can be stubborn about doing her own things; but is quick to learn and listen with consistency. Shes been the easiest to potty train and lets me know to let her outside when she needs to go; she started this on her own around 5 1/2 weeks old! She will be 8 weeks old and ready for her forever home on January 28, 2021. We are guessing that Terra might be in the 50 to 65 lbs range as an adult. (mom was 50 lbs but the puppies are quite hefty so could be larger). 

Terra's mom is Sofie who is also available for adoption. Sofie is a ~50 lb, gorgeous black Pit Bull mix with a remarkable disposition. She lives with 3 other doggies in her foster home and does well with everyone. Additionally, she adores people and is well behaved with kiddos. 

If you have the time, love and capacity to devote to Terra's development and growth, please apply at https://www.circle2rescue.com/dog-adoption-application/ The adoption fee of $500 includes the spay/neuter, vaccinations, deworming and microchip. 

Please note, Circle 2 Rescue cannot guarantee the breed, composition or ages of our dogs as we usually have no history prior to them entering the rescue. We make every effort to ensure the dogs are healthy.

animal.description:
Meet Annie! Annie is a happy girl who greets everyone with a play bow and a big grin. She is a 4 and a half year old terrier mix that weighs about 60lbs. Annie gets along well with dogs and is very submissive to even the 10lb chihuahua in her foster home. She also gets along well with the cat and chinchilla at her foster home. She loves to goof around and will adjust her play level and style based on her human and canine playmate preferences. After a good play session Annie loves to get cuddles, belly rubs and ear scratches. She can't wait for a family she can entertain!

If you are interested in any of our dogs, please complete our online adoption application:

http://www.lifesaverssp.dreamhosters.com/adoption-applicat
/

We will conduct a phone interview, check references and then a home check. This helps us to match a dog with their potential adopter. The adoption fee is $350.00 for adults and $450.00 for puppies under one year which includes spay/neutering, up-to-date age appropriate vaccinations, flea/tick & heartworm preventative and a health certificate. We foster our dogs in homes, not in shelters. This allows us to get to know the dogs temperaments in order to match them to a home. This also allows us to get the dogs ready to live in their forever homes! All dogs coming from the south have been quarantined for two weeks and fully vetted before traveling to New England!

For more info please email Lifesaversapps@outlook.com OR visit our website:

http://www.lifesaverssp.org/

animal.description:
Meet Blue Skye Lonestar AKA Blu. She is a gorgeous blue eyed beauty who is about 7 months old. We suspect that she is a Labrador, Blue Heeler and Catahoula Leopard mix. When she arrived in New Jersey, she was very fearful and felt safest in her cage. Blu has been with her foster family for four months now and she has come so far. Everyday she has making tons of progress with the help of her big canine foster brother, Bentley who is 70 pounds. He has helped tremendously in getting Blu out of her cage and she has not left his side since. It took her a bit of time to trust the humans in the house but she has doing so well. Blu can still be timid but that does not stop her from playing with everyone in the home.

Blu's forever home must consist of another dog; ideally on the larger side. Blu has a lot of energy so an active family with children over the age of 12 would be best. She loves hiking and trips to the beach. She likes to go on walks but often times gets very scared of what she hears and sees especially in crowded areas. Blu is looking for a home filled of love, patience and lots of play. When Blu plays, she can be very nippy and nibble on the back of your legs and feet; which we are attributing to the heeler in her. Blu is very excited to find her forever home and proud of herself for who she is becoming.

Apply to adopt BLUE SKYE LONESTAR at EHRdogs.org!

animal.description:
Hi ! My name is Abigail. 

I like to be called Abby. 

I am 7 years young and really just want to find a calm loving home with my new people… 

I need a little time to warm up to you but once I do, I give free kisses and love for you to rub my tummy…   

At night, I like to dive under the covers and burrow all the way to the foot of the bed to sleep…   if you are lucky, I will kiss your feet during the night to let you know I am doing ok down under.. 

I love to go on walks and am very good on the leash..  

OH and  I come with my own harness… I also have my own bed, clothes and a “dresser” to put them in… 

I pretty much come fully “ready to go”.

I have had a few accidents in the house, but only cause my foster mom didn’t know what I was trying to tell her.. and I was telling her I needed to go NOW !  but we have that figured out..  Foster mom is much happier now.. 

I do need a calm home with no kids.. sudden movements kinda scare me.. also, I do not really like being in a crate and can act out when put in one. 

But I do promise to love you unconditionally as long as you promise to do the same..  

I hope to meet my new family soon..  maybe YOU are the one

Please, if you are interested in me, put in an application with Tennessee Dachshund Rescue and reference my name…

**No kids
**Quiet home

Abby's  adoption fee will be $375.00 which includes spay, full vax, microchip, HW & parasite negative, dental (if needed) and any other medical issues treated.

Because of volume, we do not answer questions on this page.

House Trained: Yes-mostly
Crate Trained: Yes but doesn't like it
Kid Friendly: No
Cat Friendly: Unknown at this time

Abby is currently being fostered in Memphis, TN.

Adopt me, Abby at www.tndachshundrescue.com 
Please list her name on the interested in line

A little about how the adoption process works:
We are an all volunteer rescue so please be patient with us.
We usually have pre-approved adopters waiting for the right dog so it is best to get your application approved beforehand so you can contact us immediately when you are interested in meeting a potential pet.

You will be contacted once the app is processed for a home visit.
If you are already approved and see a dog you are interested in, please contact your adoption coordinator.


Check our FaceBook page at: https://www.facebook.com/tndachshundrescue/

animal.description:
12/30/20 Welcome to STAF, Aura! Her former family thought they were buying a Doodle pup. When she grew into something other than the picture they had in mind, they didn't want her anymore. Ouch. We think she's a winner no matter what her pedigree. She's around one year old (est. birth 12/19) and right around 50#. She's great in the car and loves playing with fellow pups! Please check back for updates as we get to know Aura better. Visit STAF.org for more information on our adoption process.

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions. You will be asked to return for at least one follow-up visit, then take the dog home for a trial period before officially adopting. 
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we can not adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.

Looking Glass Animal Rescue is a 501(c)(3) virtual rescue, using a network of dedicated fosters throughout the Northeast to care for our animals until adoption. You may be required to travel if approved for adoption.

Meet Shiloh and Shadow, bonded male siblings! These handsome guys are approximately 8-10 months. They are incredibly friendly and smart! Their foster has said they came without training, but do catch on quick. They are good with other dogs and kids, but have not been tested with cats. animal.description:
Gadget is about 7 years old, he weighs 8 pounds. He is spunky but not hyper. He barks when someone is at the door but he quiets quickly. He loves kibble and is a very good eater! He goes potty outside like clockwork and with a morning walk and an early evening walk and one or two quick backyard number ones, he doesn't have accidents in the house. He loves toys, but his mission is to remove the squeakers, he is obsessed with the squeakers! He is a lap dog and will snuggle for hours under a blanket. He goes right under the covers at bedtime and sleeps all night. He is also ok if he's in his kennel for periods of time. He takes a few minutes to warm up and get over his shyness but he loves people. He's been great with other dogs, but he prefers a few minutes of meet and greet before the first kiss. He is nervous when on his leash but does his business for you. He would love a backyard with a fence he can't squeeze though, he can get through my iron fence pretty easily.

To set up a meet and greet or inquire about a dog, please first fill out an application at https://savinghoperescue.org/contact. It doesn't obligate you, but it is the first step. We don't get to all of the inquiries but respond to all applications. Thank you for choosing to rescue!

animal.description:
LOOKING FOR FL ADOPTER FOR BOTH GIRLS.

CITY, STATE:  Sarasota, FL
NAME:  Emma and Pippa
AGE:  Emma: 12 yrs. (DOB 4/4/2008) ... Pippa: 9 yrs. (DOB 5/8/2011)
SEX:  Females
WEIGHT:  Emma 14.30 lbs. (needs to lose 2 lbs.) ... Pippa 10.8 lbs.
COLOR:  Emma: Blue and Tan Piebald ... Pippa: Isabella and Tan
COAT:  Both are Smooth coats
UP TO DATE:  Yes
SPAYED/NEUTERED:  Yes    DATE:  Before rescue
DHPP:  Yes    DATE:  7/30/2020
RABIES:  Yes    DATE:  7/30/2020    TAG NUMBER:  202034297 and 202034296
ADOPTION FEE:  $450 + $40 (microchip fees) for the pair     Emma alone:  $200.00+20.00 Microchip fee               Pippa alone:   $275.00+20.00 Microchip fee
HOUSETRAINED:  Yes
CRATE TRAINED:  Yes
LEASH TRAINED:  Yes
FENCED YARD NEEDED:  Yes
SPECIAL NEEDS:  No
HOME W/ SMALL CHILDREN:  Only over the age of 10 years
HOME W/ OTHER DOGS:           MALE:  Yes         FEMALE:  Yes
HOME W/ CATS:  No!
MICROCHIP BRAND and #:  911PetChip Emma 991003911206951 ... Pippa 991003911125264
MONTHLY HEARTWORM DATE:  15th of each month
FOSTER HOME:  Meg  meg1709@comcast.net
RESCUE #:  Emma 2021-01-02-01 ....  Pippa 2021-01-02-02

BIO:  Due to their recessive coloring (Blue/Tan Piebald and Isabella/Tan) Emma and Pippa will not be adopted to any state other than FL

These precious little girls came into rescue due to a toddler in their family.  Unfortunately, this is often the reason families surrender their doxies. Emma and Pippa are beyond sweet and are as lovable as can be.  It would be wonderful if one family in FL adopted both of these girls, but we will consider two families IF each adopter has another dog.  Obviously, Emma and Pippa are used to the companionship of another dog.  They are enjoying the company of their foster brother and sister, too.

What these girls need in their adoptive home:
  - No apartment or high rises
  - A fenced yard is a must, no exceptions
  - Someone home a lot as they enjoy human contact.
  - No other dog is necessary if they are adopted together, but if you only want one of the girls then you must have another small dog.
  - FL adopter due to their recessive coloring which causes thin coats (alopecia).

Emma LOVES to be with her person.  She is very quiet and so adorable with her unusual blue and tan piebald coat. Sadly, Emma lost all 31 of her remaining teeth when she had her dental.  That does not stop her from enjoying every morsel of her soften food!  She is on special diet kibble (soften and pulverized) while her gums heal and she loses 2 more lbs.  Looking on the bright side, she’ll never have to have another dental!  Oh, she does snore a little at night ... but it’s very cute!

Pippa is full of life!  If we didn’t have her DOB, we’d swear she was only 5-6 years old.  She would be so happy to have a playmate.  She never meets a stranger ... she LOVES everyone .... friendly, friendly, friendly!  Pippa lost 6 teeth at her dental including two upper canines. She loves mealtime and is first into the crate to wait for dinner to be served!  While her gum flaps heal, she is eating soften kibble.

If you’re looking for sweet, friendly, and lovable doxies, Emma and Pippa will answer your prayers!

animal.description: Who says there's no such thing as a purebred dog in a shelter? Well they're just plain wrong because I've been DNA tested and my results came back pure Catahoula Leopard Dog! Yep, my parents were Catahoulas, my parent's parents were Catahoulas and even my parent's parent's parents were Catahoulas! How's that for science?! Being true to my breed, I'm an active girl with plenty of energy to keep you on your toes. Traditionally Catahoulas were used to herd hogs and cows, so being a workin' girl and having a job (or at least plenty of exercise and activities) will keep me at my happiest. And after a long day's work, kicking back and spending some quality time with my person(s) is my idea of a great way to spend an evening. Just don't make me share you with another dog, please. I want to be your one and only, that's my only request. So how about it? Is an active girl with a big heart for her humans what you're looking for in a dog? If you said yes, then I'm your girl!

animal.description: Are you the one for me? When I came to the HSBC I arrived with injuries to my head and face. Although I couldn't tell the staff what happened to me, they knew it was traumatic. I could not see out of my right eye and there was a hole in my nasal cavity which was causing me some problems. A specialist came to visit me and did a special surgery. He fixed the hole, but had to remove my eye. I'm doing so much better now, and am spending time in a foster home where I'm getting spoiled. They say I'm a great dog, who will do best in a home with adults only or teenage kids and will do best with an experienced dog owner. I like to play with other dogs my size, my can be annoying to them if they don't want to play. Thanks to Dolly's Dream, my adoption fee is sponsored and I will get to go home with the goodies I need to settle into my new home. Please call the adoption desk at 954-989-3977 ext. 6 if you have any questions. Visit humanebroward.com to complete an adoption application and since I am in a foster home, the adoption department can schedule an appointment for you to come in and meet me with my foster mom.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Delilah is a a happy, friendly girl who is almost a year old, looking for her forever home! We're guessing she is a terrier/hound mix, but not sure. She's a petite lady though, at just about 24 lbs.

She is a curious, energetic, headstrong girl with a silly puppy personality. She still has some work to do in the house training department and she does some chewing - so, if she is to be left alone during the day a crate would be a good idea! That being said, someone who is home a lot to work with Delilah would be an ideal adopter.

Delilah is very social with other dogs and loves to play and run at the dog park. She is still learning her manners, and would best in a home with a dog that is patient and friendly with puppies... because she DOES want to play! It takes a bit to wear Delilah out, but when she settles down she loves to curl up next to you to rest. She also loves to look out the window and watch the world go by.

A home without cats would be best (she constantly chases and barks at her foster's cats!) and no small children as she's still learning her manners to not jump up.

As we learn more about her, we are thinking she might need a home with a fenced in yard and another dog.

Your Pyrents liked you being outside and doing chores with them around the alpaca and having free roam of the 5 acre property. You were a good girl to sleep in your crate at night - which was safer for the other dogs in the house!

All we need to do now is find you just the right home to appreciate all of your finer qualities - and I'm sure we can do that.

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

This handsome 2.5 year-old dog with the bobtail is Rally who looks to be a mix of Aussie and Corgi. He was surrendered to a county dog shelter in February 2020 by his family who could no longer care for him. We don't know what circumstances led to him losing his home but the shelter was told that Rally had seizures in the past but was not on any medication. From the shelter, he went into a foster home where he was observed closely for over a month and no seizures were seen. Rally then made the trip to Canine Lifeline in late March 2020 so he could find himself the perfect new home. He was adopted from us in April 2020 but recently returned (Jan 2021) because he never became completely comfortable with the man in the home. Rally is going to need a home with a dog-savvy single woman who can provide the exercise and training that this active young dog needs. Rally only had one mild seizure in the 9 months he was in his most recent home. No medication is prescribed unless the seizures become more frequent. Rally is crate-trained and and has good house manners in his foster home so should be able to pick up the house rules quickly in his new home. He gets along well with other dogs and likes playing with them so might enjoy having a playful canine buddy in his new home or regular trips to doggie daycare. Rally loves tennis balls and toys but does exhibit some resource guarding according to his previous owner so his new owner will need to continue working with him on that and managing the situation to set him up for success. Rally walks nicely on a leash and would make a great hiking, walking, or jogging buddy. Being a herding breed, Rally needs a lot of physical exercise and mental stimulation each day. We do want to place him in a home that has a yard with a secure aboveground fence so he can run and play to his heart's content. Rally weighs about 38 pounds and his adoption fee is $325. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Rally. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Rally and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH. 2/1/21 1:42 PM

animal.description:
Bowser here!
I love my new foster home, there are so many things for me to explore. I love the dog beds, playing with all the other dogs big and small in the house, trying to climb the cat tree and stealing my foster moms shoes (yum). I love to play, whether it be with another pup or a toy then I love to nap in the dog bed with my brother.
I have enough energy to keep up with the big doggos, and have no fear when we are inside playing. I am still trying to figure out this cold outdoors thing, not my fav but I do sometimes go potty out there and love to find leaves and sticks to chew on.
I live with 2 dogs and 2 cats and have been good with both. I am working on crate training and potty training right now but both are coming along!

PLEASE READ COMPLETELY 

All of our kids are being raised in volunteer foster homes, so we do not have a single location to visit. You will need to submit an application to be approved for a Meet and Greet.

If you are interested in adopting or more information please do the following before contacting Path of Hope: 

1. Go to our website www.pathofhoperescue.com 
2. Thoroughly read through the FAQ section on the "Adopt" page (this will answer most questions!)
3. If you are still interested, fill out an online application on our website and our Matchmaker will be in touch with you! 
4. Follow us on facebook, https://www.facebook.com/pathofhoperescue/ , to see lots of cute puppy photos. learn about puppy events, and get updates on the rescue!

Our adoption fee for puppies is $400 and includes age appropriate core vaccines, minimum two rounds of dewormer, microchip with free registration and spay/neuter surgery. A refund of $100 is available with completion of any training class.

animal.description:
Our grumpy little man. Burgy came to us with a pretty significant set of dog bite wounds. His first day he had a drain placed in his arm from our “Dogter”. He has healed so well!! 

Burgy is a 1 year old shar pei mix. He is very hesitant of making new human friends but he does come around. He may bark at first. . Because of this we require a child free home! No growling dogs in a house with kids please!  He’s gotten to know and love the staff and volunteers and we have loved this smooshy faced boy right back. 

Because of his dog bites, Burgy doesn’t want any dog friends ?. We recommend he is the only dog. We do not know how he is with other animals. Please bring them in a hard carrier for a meet. 

He will need a home who is willing to work on his socialization. Not every human is bad and he would do amazing with some professional training toward other dogs. 

When you adopt a dog, PLEASE research decompression. This is key to a dog adapting to a home.

animal.description:
Tiki is a very sweet and active young dog. She can be shy with strangers but as soon as a treat is offered, she is your new best friend and cannot get enough petting and playing. Her family did not have the time for an active heeler breed, so Tiki spent a lot of time alone.  She was surrendered so that she could find a home with a yard to romp in, where there is plenty of time for her to learn good manners.  

Tiki is a very sweet girl and learns very quickly. She knows a few commands but will benefit from gentle yet firm positive feedback training. Tiki is always happy to have people around her and is very playful, but she can be selective in choosing her canine friends.

Tiki is about one year old and weighs 40 pounds.

If you would like to meet Tiki, or find out more, please call (707) 884-1304 and leave a message, or send an email to redwoodcoasthumane@gmail.com. Dogs are shown by appointment only, so please make arrangements in advance.

Redwood Coast Humane Society dog adoptions cost $100.00 which includes all age-appropriate vaccinations, and spay/neuter.

ALL PETS AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION ONLY TO RESIDENTS OF THE DALLAS/FT WORTH METROPLEX

MEET AND GREET APPOINTMENTS SET UP WITH PRE-APPROVED APPLICATION ONLY

Puppy Policies: We do not adopt puppies under 6 months of age into apartment homes. All children in the home must be at least 5 years of age. We appreciate your understanding of these policies. 

Cupid is the only girl in her litter of brothers and she loves nothing more than wrestling with them and playing chase. She is smart, cute, and she adores chew toys! We rescued her mom Ginger from South TX and we found out when she arrived that she was pregnant. She had 5 healthy babies who have thrived in their foster home. Their mom weighs approx 40 lbs and appears to be a hound/terrier mix so that is our best guess on size and breed. After Cupid finishes playing then it is cuddle time with her foster family but she is hoping to find a forever home soon to share her cuddles with .... could it be with you? 

Like all puppies, Cupid needs an adopter who is willing to train and work with her to help her be the best dog she can be.

If you would like to meet Cupid, the first step in the process is to complete an application.  Please go to roadtrip4paws.com and click on the Adopt tab to find a link to our online application.  

Home visits required for all dog adoptions

animal.description:
Meet Zinzi! 

This beautiful Rottie was on the euthanasia list due to no fault of her own. We don’t know how she ended up a stray but we did know we couldn’t let her lose her life and have humans fail her again. 

Zinzi was estimated to be around 6 years old by the shelter. She is a rather plump gal weighing around 120 pounds. She could definitely benefit from shedding a few pounds- maybe lose that Covid weight together for summer? Because she will be a larger gal even after losing some pounds, the shelter thinks she was used for breeding. We will never know, but we do know she deserves the best life! 

Because of her size, and probable lack of being ever loved and treated at as a family dog, we are recommending a home without young children. She does well with meeting teenagers and adults but has not met a young child yet. Zinzi is also not the biggest fan of being in her crate. She is much happier outside of a crate hanging and lounging with her people. 

At this time we are requiring her forever family to be familiar with her breed. 
If you are interesting in fostering or adopting Zinzi, please visit our website to fill out an application! 
www.safewithusanimalrescue.org

animal.description:
Beluga is a energetic young lady who is looking for a fun and active household who can keep up with her puppy antics. Beluga absolutely loves people as well as other
dogs
, though her enthusiasm may be a bit much for cats, small dogs, and children under 12 years old. Beluga values her playtime more than anything else, so we are requiring that she go to a home with another active and tolerant large dog. Beluga will need an owner who is committed to helping her with basic training and manners, she can get a bit mouthy when she is excited, but she means no real harm. This adorable pooch has quite a bit of energy to burn, so a home with a yard would be ideal for her to zoom around in. Beluga is crate trained and housebroken, though she may have a few accidents for the first few days in a new home.

Age: 6-8 months

How I came to PAWS: Surrendered due to landlord issues

Animal ID#: 48941

Weight: 42 lbs

Mixed breed (It's impossible to identify breed mix by sight alone, so for most dogs, their mix is only a guess. We get to know each dog as an individual and strive to make matches based on personality, not on breed label.)

Location: Foster Care

All our dog meets are by appointment only; to get started, please complete the adoption application. To learn more about this dog, please contact us at adoptions@phillypaws.org or 215-298-9680 ext. 16._____________________________________
To adopt a cat, complete the application at phillypaws.org/catapp.To adopt a dog, complete the application at phillypaws.org/dogapp.
Please reference this animal's ID NUMBER when inquiring.
Learn more about PAWS' adoption process, locations, and more at: phillypaws.org/adopt/info.
__________________________________________Adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, spay/neuter, and microchip. Adoption fees are as follows, plus tax: $150 for large adult dogs (older than 1 year); $250 for small dogs (under 25 lbs) and all puppies (under 1 year); $60 for adult cats (over 6 months of age), and $100 for kittens (under 6 months of age). When you adopt a pair of kittens together, the total adoption fee is $150.
PAWS, the Philadelphia Animal Welfare Society, is a 501(c)3 non-profit animal rescue organization dedicated to saving Philadelphia's homeless and at-risk animals. PAWS is the city's largest rescue partner and provider of low-cost, basic veterinary care. Through our adoption locations, special events, and network of foster homes, PAWS finds loving homes for thousands of animals every year. PAWS is working to make Philadelphia a no-kill city where every healthy and treatable pet is guaranteed a home. Please visit www.phillypaws.org for more information on adopting, fostering, volunteering, or donating.

He enjoys head pets and scratching, which he shows you through his special Moe smile.

If you would like to meet Moe or any of our other pets, to find out more, please call (707) 884-1304 and leave a message, or send an email to redwoodcoasthumane@gmail.com. Dogs are shown by appointment only, so please make arrangements in advance.

Redwood Coast Humane Society dog adoptions cost $100.00 which includes all age-appropriate vaccinations, and spay/neuter.

Jiro is about 5 years old. He is a sweet fellow who is good with other kids and dogs. We do not know what he thinks of cats. Jiro weighs about 39 pounds.

We do NOT ship our animals. All adoptive families must travel to us to meet their adoptive dog/cat. Applicants must live within a 2 hour radius from Sparta/Andover (07871/07821).

Please understand that we are an animal shelter and thus unable to say whether the dogs are housebroken as they are not in homes.

If you are interested in adopting, we encourage you to please submit an application on our website today so that we can try and process and pre-approve any potential adopters prior to our next adoption event.

PLEASE USE THIS LINK TO SUBMIT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION. WE ONLY ACCEPT ADOPTION APPLICATIONS THROUGH OUR WEBSITE. ANY OTHERS WILL NOT BE PROCESSED.
Application link here: http://www.oscaranimalrescue.org/oscar-1-application.html

Adoption Process:
1.Fill out an application
2.Meet & Greet
3.Adoption contract & adoption fee
Jiro's adoption fee is $350. This also covers all age-appropriate shots, spay/neuter, vetting & microchipping.

**If you are coming to an adoption event to see a certain dog/cat, please email ahead of time to make sure that dog/cat will be there that day. Please email 1-2 days before the event, as some animals are placed during the week and our list is constantly changing.
For a list of upcoming pet adoption events go to: www.OscarAnimalRescue.org

One Step Closer Animal Rescue is a 501c3 non-profit organization. Donations are TAX DEDUCTIBLE to the extent allowed by law. If you would like to make a donation to help us rescue more animals please send donations to PO Box 248, Sparta, NJ 07871. Please make your check payable to O.S.C.A.R.. animal.description:
Bumble is a gorgeous, female mix dog who is 5 years old and weighs 45 lbs. She is spayed, up to date on shot. Bumble does well with dogs, children and cats. Bumble will be a little shy at first, but will quickly warm up to her new family. She is crate trained, potty trained and does well on a leash.

Bumble was rescued by the Houston SPCA from an extreme neglect situation in Texas. Due to the years of neglect, she has tested heartworm positive. She is under the care of a vet in Texas, and will come with the slow kill heartworm medicine needed to complete her treatment (8-12 months) 

Bumble has come a very long way from when she was rescued- she had severe mange (so much that she was almost completely hairless) and was starving to death. She has made almost a full recovery from her dire situation and she now  has a clean bill of health and so deserves a family to call her own!   Bumble would love the chance to feel safe, warm and loved for the rest of her life. The last picture shows how far sweet Bumble has come!


She comes with her medical records as well as the medication required to complete her heartworm treatment.  Our dogs also come with free 30-days of health insurance which reimburses you for any vet you use for illnesses and injuries which commence during that period, as per the directions in the flier which comes in your adoption packet.


If you are serious about adopting Bumble, please contact us at DogTrailRides@gmail.com or text or call 832-338-7041 or 281-844-7140. We take payments through Zelle, Venmo, PayPal, CashApp, or we can take card numbers over the phone and process them through Square. All of these methods provide a receipt.

Thank you for supporting our efforts! 
We cannot guarantee breed. We assign breed designations based on veterinary advice and information from the prior owner.

animal.description:
Gibby is very friendly with people likes car rides going on walks and runs and taking naps. He is good in the house and prefers to be inside during the day. He is house trained and exhibits no destructive behavior to belongings or furniture. He likes to be with people all day. He has had no signs of aggression when I've had him. He is a gentle guy and very trainable. He knows 'sit' and 'leave it' and is very obedient. Best to be homed as a single dog or with a well adjusted friendly large dog.
Gibson's exercise needs are low maintenance for his breed. He will sleep at your feet while you work from home for or watch you cook and do chores. I work full time and take him out in the evenings and mornings and that seems to be enough to keep him satisfied. He would be a great companion. I suspect he would like to run around with another furry companion if I had one for him. He seems very excited when he sees a friendly big dog!
He does have separation anxiety but is manageable because he just wants a person with him. I hardly ever leave him alone except for short periods (10-15 minutes) but mainly lots of barking and trying to go through door or window to get to me. When left in the backyard for some time while knowing you're inside ( I watch him from a large window ) he will sleep by the door. He mainly wants to be by you. If there is another human out there he will follow them though- very friendly. He could benefit from crate training but I think it will take time. I have a crate for him and we are working on it. He wanted to get out when I put him in. Lots of barking when left alone even for short periods of time He needs a human to feel secure- not necessarily the owner. I have had friend and grandfather watch him and he doesn't react the same way. He gets a little sad but no barking and warms up to whose with him.
He presents prey drive - someone familiar with the husky breed will be a great match! No small animals cats or rural areas near livestock.
We are helping Gibby's current guardian to rehome him. Please fill out our online application and we will forward to them. Adoption fee would be minimum $100 donation to Furry Friends Rescue. If you have specific questions please send them through and we will put you in touch with his current guardian.

animal.description: Raider is a big ole' sweet, loveable cuddle bug! He's got a permanent smirk because he just can't stop smiling and boy is it big and beautiful especially when we spend some time with him! Our big boy Raider is about 7 years old, but don't let his age fool you! When he gets excited he acts like a puppy! You'll see him jumping around, smiling with his tongue out and wagging his tail like crazy all while giving us some happy wiggles. After he gets all his fun time and tires out, Raider seems to think he's a lap dog! He'll come up to you after a day of play and lay right in your lap like a big ole baby. He'll probably look up at you with his puppy dog eyes asking for a treat or two. Did we mention he loves treats? He'll do just about anything for some tasty treats! Raider is very friendly towards people! Raider does good with big dogs, he just likes to take it real slow. He does seem to prefers people over other animals. He much rather be the only dog in a house hold. Raider isn't very fond of smaller animals so we recommend he goes to a home without any. Come visit with him and witness his happy wiggles!! He is heartworm positive but his treatment is included with his adoption fee and will be administered at the shelter!

animal.description:
Apply to Adopt Me!

Romeo had a sad beginning to his life. He was born as a breeder pup, confined to a small bathroom for the first year of his life. No one has taken the time to potty train him, so he has lived at a couple different homes. His last owner was going to dump him at her vet to be euthanized because she couldn't potty train him. So luckily he found his way into our rescue. Romeo is a super sweet almost 6-year-old boy who weighs 11 lbs. He gets along great with all people, dogs and cats, and is friendly when meeting new people. He is very playful, and loves to play with soft squeaky toys. He does sometimes get playful-nippy when playing. He loves to cuddle and be held. He sleeps well through the night (loves sleeping under the covers), with an occasional need to go out in the middle of the night. He knows "sit" and patiently waits for treats. He walks well on a harness and leash, but needs a soft harness that doesn't irritate his skin. He rides great in the car in a doggy booster seat. He has immature cataracts that minimally affect his vision. We don't know if his cataracts are congenital or if they will worsen. As mentioned, he is not fully potty trained. His foster mom has been working on his potty training, and he will go potty outside when taken out. Although he is not fully potty trained, he is smart and a fast learner, and with continued love, time and patience, we believe he will learn.

Therefore, someone who works from home would be ideal for him so that he could be taken out often. He is also missing several teeth and requires soft food. We are looking for an adult-only home for him, and a home with another playful pup close to his size. An adopter who has breed experience is preferred, and we are requiring a fenced-in yard because Romeo loves to run.

Being a Chinese Crested Hairless means he has hair on his head, legs and tail. The Crested is prone to more frequent skin irritations, allergies and sunburn than a coated dog would experience, and his owner should always take precautions to prevent this. Although no dog is truly 'hypoallergenic,' Cresteds shed little to no hair and are on AKC's list of breeds recommended for those with allergies. If you live in the central Florida (Orlando) area, match ALL of his qualifications, and think you have the perfect forever home for Romeo, we'd love to find out more about you. Please fill in our adoption application and we'll see if you're Romeo's perfect match.

animal.description:
Hi I’m Juliet!! I am a sweet and beautiful 2 yr old Labrador mix about 53 lbs.  I’m a little shy at first, but once I get to know you my heart will shine through! I’m learning how wonderful life can be with my foster mama - I’ve missed all the attention, love and cuddles so far but I’m ready to get caught up! In fact, I’ve just found out how wonderful belly rubs are, and I’ll roll over for you as soon as we are friends.  I’m great with other dogs and love running and playing with all my pup friends.  My foster mama is a little biased, but she says I’m really smart - I’m learning my manners and working on how to walk on a leash.  I’m a romantic and I believe in love at first sight – do you? 

*All of The Right to Live dogs are fostered locally in San Antonio Texas and will be transported to other states to their new families upon adoption. We believe fostering dogs and not having them decompress in a kenneled environment is more beneficial for the dogs and builds their trust and companionship in a family situation. Adoption fee includes transportation costs, previous/current medical treatment (spay/neuter, etc.) and a health certificate for cross-state travel*

animal.description:
*ADOPTER OR FOSTER NEEDED ASAP*
 
Hey friends!  I'm Hercules!  I recently found my way from the streets into this shelter.  While it is nice to have food and a bed and some awesome people who take me out for walks, I would really love to find a loving place I can call home.
 
Even though I am still learning to be gentle and that I am bigger than I think, I love all humans!  But I do prefer the older ones, teenagers and older that is, because I don't realize that I am super strong.  I always show when I am excited because I have a cute wiggly butt and I shake it like a Polaroid picture!
 
I do love going for walks and I am also getting better every time about listening to the human walking with me.  After my initial excitement of the walk, I will be right with you!  Sometimes I will jump up and I use whatever I can to get your attention, but I am working on that too, because I am a beast and I am being told not all humans like a giant lap dog!  I do also tend to be vocal when I'm playing, but I'm just so excited and I want you to know that!
 
I know how to sit and I know down, I also like getting treats when I do things right!  But I prefer if you set the treat on the ground or toss it my way!
 
When I meet new dogs, I like to learn a LOT about them, so I do need help learning how to meet new dogs properly.  Can you help me do that?  I love them, but I think because I am big, I kind of scare them a little bit. 


Please help us get Hercules into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!
 
If you would like to adopt loving Hercules, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

animal.description:
Adoptable in NJ/ PA
Dog's Name: 
Sheena

Dog's Age: 
3 years old (DOB 4/08/2017)

Perfect Household Includes:
Ideally Sheena's primary caregiver would be male. Sheena 100% likes both men and women (her foster is a woman), she is just a bit boy crazy and it's adorable... literally falling over onto her back for belly rubs from men and just squishes into them. If we're talking perfect, she would probably love being an only dog to get all the spoils to herself but has been friendly with all dogs of all shapes and sizes that she has met so far and lives with. 

Personality Traits:
Sheena is really overall a good dog and listens to corrections very well. Through continued training and clear consistent boundaries she will blossom into the best friend you've been missing. In the short time in her foster home she has been transforming rapidly. 
She is a happy squishy girl with a bit of a take charge attitude. She puts her weight into everything she does, her love, her walks, her play, sitting on your feet, everything. the ideal home would not have small children or others that are physically unstable. They should be able to lift/push/pull her weight. Sheena is working on getting her slim figure back. Her ideal weight is in the 50/55 pound range, but she’s currently clocking in around 75 pounds. She is housebroken, making improvements on her walks and very smart.

Fun Fact:
Sheena makes the best faces and is hilarious. She LOVES a good butt scratch and will back that booty up for it any chance she gets. She also snores and it’s adorable!

Special Needs:
Sheena will need ongoing, firm, consistent and patient training and boundaries. She is making progress on her boundaries, sharing and not having to run the show. As her trust grows with her foster, this does get better. She is beginning to seek love in lieu of attention and the payoff has been priceless. 

Sheena is working on crate training, has 2 scheduled naps a day and sleeps in her crate through the night. When told "time for a nappy" - she hardly makes a peep when in there and will now go in on her own from time to time for a nappy.

Apply here: https://www.emailmeform.com/builder/form/ICY0zLb5eMAfRd8dptd7

animal.description:
Meet Panda. He is a Great Pyreness Bully Breed mix ready for an active home. He is a big goofy boy that would love an active home. He enjoys playing with toys and tug of war. He would do great in a home with lots of space for him to play.  Panda has been picky with his canine friends while at the shelter so we always suggest a meet and greet with any dog currently in your home. Panda's adoption fee is $250. Contact the shelter at 920-835-1738 or email ocontoareahumane@gmail.com to set up an appointment to adopt. At this time we are only doing adoptions via appointment.

CATS: Undetermined.  
DOGS: Can be picky with other dog buddies.  Meet and greet required. 
KIDS: Undetermined. but has lived with them in past.



OAHS is able to accommodate same day adoptions.  The adoptions are based on a first-come basis providing it is a good match for everyone involved. 
The first step in the adoption process is to complete our adoption questionnaire to ensure we can help find the right fit for you.  An adoption interview is required prior to adoption.  An Adoption Counselor will ask about your residence, family members and pet experience.  The Adoption Counselor will also address any concerns and answer any questions that you may have about adding a new pet to your family.

OAHS is State of Wisconsin licensed and inspected: 268244-DS.

Many area veterinarians are offering a free health exam and/or other discounted services for pets adopted from a humane society. Please contact your local vets regarding any applicable discounts.   

OAHS is open Monday 1-5pm, Wednesday 1-6pm, Friday 1-5pm, Saturday 11am-3pm, and Sunday 11am-3pm.  We are located at 150 S. Katch Avenue behind the Oconto Veterinary Center in Oconto, Wisconsin. From Hwy 41, go west onto Hwy 22, north onto Van Hecke Avenue, and east onto S. Katch Avenue.

animal.description:
Reba is a beautiful 6-7 month old lab mix that will be joining AHR from our Louisiana partner shelter.  She currently weighs 33 lbs.

She was surrendered to our partner shelter with alopecia all over her body.  She has regained a healthier coat!  

Her Louisiana foster Mom brings her to work regularly at her vet clinic and says she does well with the people. Does well with dogs of all sizes and cats. Kennel, leash and house trained. Can be a little shy at first but once she warms up, she is very loving

Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

animal.description:
Hi there,

I'm my name is Autumn.   Although I am very young, I think that Autumn would be my favorite season of the year.  So many fun things happen then like festivals and trick or treating, and of course, Thanksgiving!!  Hmm, I wonder if I like turkey...of course I do what was I thinking??  

So, my 7 siblings and I were dumped along with our mommy when we were only 2 months old.  I'm sad and confused at how somebody could be so mean and cruel to do such a thing like that.  Mommy would lick us and soothe us and tell us it would be ok, but I know she was very sad and heartbroken as well :(

As luck would have it, we got dumped in front of a house where a family's grand daughter was visiting.  When she saw us, she went running into the house to her grandparents crying.  She was so worried about us and wanted to take us in.  Sweet Granny caved and allowed the grand daughter to care for us.  

Guess what that grand daughter did?  She got to work and found homes for some of us!  Granny then called the wonderful peeps at Lucies Project to see if they could take in the rest of us.  Well, of course they did!!  They are super duper awesomely amazing!!!

As you can see,  I am a cute puppy full of love, character and energy.  I would love to come live with you and claim you as my furever family.  What do you say??  Pwease???

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
****Please do not message the rescue asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO BEFORE EMAILING****

*Name: Rosalie
*Age: 2 yrs
*Current Weight: 65 lbs
*Adoption fee: $300

Rosalie is super super sweet and loves her person!  She is wonderful with kids. She is still a puppy and requires supervision when out of her crate. She will self-play if alone and loves to chew on her toys and her bones.  She has short bursts on energy then rests, and loves to swim! Swimming is a great exercise for her and will help her to stay physically fit as her knee joints underwent reconstruction.  She is not in any pain and loves to run and play. She loves other dogs and we would love her to go to a home where she has another doggie companion! She will guard her bones, but has no issue sharing toys with others.  She will not do well on long hikes but daily walks and play at the park or simply in the house/yard will keep this pup happy and content with her family! 

We do prefer she goes to a home with someone home most of the time (even after Covid is under control!) and with a fenced-in yard.

To apply to adopt Rosalie, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.** 

*Health: up to date on required vaccines, spayed, Was born with her rear limbs twisted from the knees down. She had difficulty standing and fully using her rear limbs before, but she's had bilateral TPLO surgery & is rehabbed & continues to get stronger! She can run, play, sit as best as possible but there are some limitations that remain.

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING
-------------------------------------------------------
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Hello! I'm Carlisle and I'm full of ADVENTURE! I'm a German Shorthaired Pointer and everyone thinks I'm between 1 and 2 years old. I still need neutered. I LOVE other dogs and don't fully trust humans yet. 

I was running around on my own for at least 3 months before anyone was able to capture me. After about a few days in captivity (what the humans call a 'foster home') I was able to break my collar and run free again for almost a week! I need a place that can keep me safe and secure while I settle back down and learn how to trust humans again. 

______________________

We are looking for a foster-to-adopt situation for Carlisle. 

We need someone who:
-Has breed experience with a German Shorthaired Pointer or very similar breed.
-Has a VERY tall, SOLID and SECURE fenced backyard. The more land for him to run on, the better. But the secure fence is the most important part.
-Has at least one other dog. He LOVES all dogs and will not do well in a house without one.
-Is willing to spend a lot of time being extremely patient with Carlisle since he is the highest order of flight risk. He has been trapped twice and if he gets out again, he may be too smart to get captured a third time.

Oreo is an adorable 2.5 month old male puppy that will be arriving to AHR from our partner shelter in Louisiana, along with his sister Cocoa.  

He plays well with other dogs and loves squeaky toys, great snuggler, loves playing outside and is active.


Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

animal.description:
Meet Leia!

10-year-old Leia was brought to Long Beach Shelter as a stray and then became a Frosted Face on January 5th. She is so sweet! Leia is vision impaired and has an enlarged heart, but no signs of heart failure yet. Leia has been cleared by our vet to have much-needed dental surgery. Her little mouth will feel so much better afterwards!

Leia is currently on a 2-week Frosted Fling so we can learn more about her in a home environment. She is really blossoming! Her Fling Mom reported in with what she's learned about Leia: She is potty trained! She uses the grass patch on her Fling Mom's apartment balcony and also goes to a local park for short walks several times a day. Leia is described as independent, mellow, and happy. She's not a lap dog, but likes to be the same room with her Fling Mom and asks for uppies and cuddles in the evening. Leia also loves belly rubs! She is a smart cookie who despite being vision impaired, learned the layout of her Fling home quickly. On walks, she's inquisitive and likes to explore everything. When at home, Leia naps often, but if there is something going on she's right there to check it out! She can be a spunky girl. City noises, elevators, dogs or people do not bother her. She enjoys new things and is engaged. Leia wants to be a part of the action! On her Fling, Leia has met plenty of dogs of all sizes, no issues. She has also done very well with her Frosted Face Fling brother. It seems like Leia would really enjoy having a doggie sibling in her forever home.

What's next on Leia's Fling itinerary? She will be having her dental soon and has a spa day scheduled at the groomers! Her Fling Mom shares, "Leia is really settling in. She's showing her great, sweet, and loving personality! I think she's just perfect and isnready for a fabulous loving family to cherish her!"

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Barbie is Chihuahua mix who will be joining us from Texas on January 5th. She was found abandoned in a home after the renters moved out and has been in a foster home in Texas. She is a happy-go-lucky girl who likes other dogs and kids. She will make a great companion for someone who likes activity and a couch potato dog. We will post more info as we get to know her.

Seattle Foster Update:
Barbie is an absolute doll (no pun intended :) She is outgoing, silly, and full of personality. It wasn't long after she arrived that her tail was wagging and she was rolling around on fury blankets for the best possible back scratch. She has settled in seamlessly in her foster home. She is currently in a foster home with two other small breed dogs, but would prefer to be in a forever home as the only pup. She has been accompanying her mom to work a few times and has shown to be a great office companion - quickly winning over the hearts of all her coworkers. She has a great snuggly side to her where she will take an opening to crawl into your lap, or lounge right beside you. She is a cute sleeper with a faint snore :) She has great energy for walks and exploring, so don't let her small frame fool you. Barbie is looking for a committed forever home that can continue to work on her training. Barbie does need firm boundaries and a strong leader, to help curb some of her insecure behaviors. She can get a little possessive of her humans, so it's important she is a home that knows to set rules and boundaries with her.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $475, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, and heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was rescued by Second Chance Dog Rescue in Texas and transferred via Project Freedom Ride. This dog will be available for adoption in Seattle once evaluated.

animal.description:
DALLAS TEXAS

Meet Harriette.  She is a 3 yo spayed female Anatolian Shepherd x Great Pyrenees cross.
Harriette's estimated DOB is Jan 2018.
She weighs appx 80 lbs
Harriette has recently had her final injection for heartworm treatment and is expected to make a full recovery with no adverse effects.

Harriette was originally rescued from Louisiana last fall just before Hurricane Delta hit.  She is now ready for her very own family!

Harriette is a super sweet girl who is looking for a person/family who knows and understands flock guardian dogs such as Anatolians and Pyrenees.
She loves her family but is often not welcoming to strangers and visitors so she is going to be
happiest in a home with low foot traffic and a quiet environment.
She may do best as the only dog, however she could possibly do well with a laid back male dog who is her size or larger.

Harriette is housebroken and responds to basic commands as well as any Anatolian will!  She needs a yard with secure fencing as she loves to go outside and patrol the area.

Harriette is not a candidate for a working home and she is not a candidate for an apartment home.

Adoption is limited to homes within the state of Texas.

For more information please email asdrescue@gmail.com

animal.description: Gloria is a very special dog. She originally came to us because she was left tied to a pole. Although this dog has been through abandonment and who know what else, she is a smiling sweetie. You would never know that happened to her because she is a very friendly and outgoing! Gloria appears to be a shepherd mix of some sort but she is on the smaller side for a shepherd. She likes walks, exploring, and playing with her Chuck-it balls. She walks well on the leash and is always looking forward to her next one. Gloria was adopted from us before but it didn't work out, so she was returned. She wanted to be the only dog in the house and her new family would need to meet that requirement. If your household includes cats, Gloria will fit right in. Her previous owners told us that Gloria didn't have issues with the cats and would do fine with them again. In the home she lived in, she was a good girl with going outside and was considered housebroken. She did not destroy things in the house or yard and is crate trained. If you think I would be a good fit for you and your family, please make an appointment and come visit her today!

animal.description:
Fun Facts about Cora:

Enjoys walks, fresh air and sunshine

Is playful with other dogs

Trying hard to be brave

Cora will come up to you for pets and attention

Is learning crate training and loves it!



Challenges for Cora:

She needs to go to a family with another more confident dog, to help Cora

Fearful in new situations







You can learn more about the organization that rescued me here: http://nmdr.org

 - - - - - -

Prior to being rescued, many of our dogs have experienced minimal socialization. As a result, there is often an adjustment period when learning about life as a family pet. We typically do not adopt to homes with children under 6 years old; homes with older children will be considered on an individual basis. Common skills such as house training and leash walking will often take a little extra time. Patience, understanding and a gentle hand are a must. The great news is, most of these dogs come around rather quickly and being a part of their rehabilitation is an extremely rewarding experience. Learn about mill dogs and fill out an application at our website: http://nmdr.org

animal.description:
Tank is a super hunky boy looking for a new place to park his toys!   He was found last summer by good samaritans tied up in a dog park in Brooklyn.   He was emaciated, had a severe urinary infection and was extremely dehydrated.

We had a prior adopter who had recently lost her dog.    She kindly opened her heart and home to Tank to give him a forever home.  Unfortunately she suffered a serious back injury and had to leave her job.    Tank is just too strong for her to manage comfortably, so she has made the heart-wrenching decision to find him a more suitable home.

When Tank was originally found, due to his poor condition, the vets originally thought he was 7 to 8 years old.    Now that he’s recovered and healthy as a horse, we believe he’s not more than 4 years old.  He is a large-boned boy and extremely strong.    He does need some work on the leash.  He is a super-energetic boy who would benefit from having a large fenced in yard to run in and play.

Tank seems to prefer women over men.    As we don’t know his background prior to being adopted, we plan to have him evaluated by a trainer friend to see if he was just being protective of his owner or he just does not care for men. 
We are seeking a home with no other pets, experienced German Shepherd owners and no children.    Although he has been good with his owner’s grandchildren, he is a large dog who loves to show his love for those he cares about and he could quite possibly knock someone down.

Please fill out an application if you are interested in the very special boy.

animal.description:
Hey folks my name is Tammy and I'm a laid-back kind a girl. I'm not really into being picked up and cuddled on, I prefer to cuddle up in a comfy dog bed or with a pillow and blanket on the floor. I realize my snoring can be hard to sleep with so I don't even mind sleeping in the living room by myself as long as it's comfy and cozy.

I'm about 8 years old and weigh around 15 lbs. I do OK with other dogs my size as long as they're not into my food. I really like my food and don't like to share it under any circumstances.

I like to go outside and wander around the fenced yard at my foster home and I really try hard to do my business out there, although sometimes I can't hold it overnight I need to use a potty pad. You can trust me to be left alone because I don't really get into things, I kind of prefer to just sleep.

I promise I'm not really much trouble I just need a safe space to lay my head and to be fed daily. Once I get comfortable with you I'm OK with you petting me, I just prefer to keep my feet on the ground and not be picked up. I prefer to explore around at my own pace. If my new family doesn't have a fenced yard, I will walk on a leash but let's keep my walk short because I'm not much in to lengthy exercise ;)

Tammy is spayed, microchipped, current on annual vaccines, heartworm negative.

Her adoption fee is $250, home visit and vet reference required. Please apply to start the approval process.

He is a sucker for a good squeaky toy, tennis ball or anything you want to throw his way. He is young and eager to learn. Zack is housebroken and working on basic obedience. If you are interested in any of our dogs, please complete our online adoption application:

http://www.lifesaverssp.dreamhosters.com/adoption-applicat
/

We will conduct a phone interview, check references and then a home check. This helps us to match a dog with their potential adopter. The adoption fee is $350.00 for adults and $450.00 for puppies under one year which includes spay/neutering, up-to-date age appropriate vaccinations, flea/tick & heartworm preventative and a health certificate. We foster our dogs in homes, not in shelters. This allows us to get to know the dogs temperaments in order to match them to a home. This also allows us to get the dogs ready to live in their forever homes! All dogs coming from the south have been quarantined for two weeks and fully vetted before traveling to New England!

For more info please email Lifesaversapps@outlook.com OR visit our website:

http://www.lifesaverssp.org/
